disambiguation: Middle member of the saxophone family
description: The most common member of the saxophone family, it is the alto member.
name: alto saxophone

description: The gayageum is a traditional Korean zither-like string instrument which normally has 12 strings.
name: gayageum

description: Reedless aerophone, usually a tube.
name: flute

description: Folk-fiddle from Hardanger, Norway. It has 4 melody- and 4-5 drone-strings, it is richly decorated and used in the traditional "halling" folk music and dance.
name: hardingfele

description: The alto clarinet is a clarinet in E♭ or sometimes F, normally with a curved neck.
name: alto clarinet

description: The most famous member of the violin family, it is actually the "small viol". Its register is soprano and it's a principal member of the symphony orchestra.
name: violin

disambiguation: Baroque fretless similar to both viols and violins.
description: While it is fretless and played like the violins "a la braccia", it has a flat back, c-holes and sloping shoulders like a viol. From the baroque period, it has up to 14 strings.
name: viola d'amore

description: Mexican vihuela, used by mariachi bands.
name: Mexican vihuela

description: The alphorn, or alpine horn, is a conical wood horn used for communication in mountains.
name: alphorn

description:
Developed in the 16th century, these violas da braccio are distinct from the viola da gamba family.
Modern members are:
  • Violin (little viola)
  • Viola
  • Violoncello (small big viola)
  • Double Bass (replacing the violone (big viola))
Past members include the violone (now considered a viol) and bass viol (a forerunner to the violoncello). Occasionally Octobass is also included as a member.
name: violin family

description: The baritone horn is a piston valve brass instrument with a wide-rimmed cup mouthpiece which is pitched in B♭, one octave below the B♭ trumpet.
name: baritone horn

description: Generally any bowed handle lute with the characteristic "violin" shape belong to fiddles.
name: fiddle

description: Early 19th century brass instrument with a conical bore, it is more compact and mellower than the trumpet which it resembles.
name: cornet

description: The bass clarinet is a clarinet, typically pitched an octave below the soprano B♭ clarinet.
name: bass clarinet

description: Any kind of instrument with membranes, usually variously sized drums.
annotation: to be working with these for now:    Cylindrical drums		) possibly combine    Conical drums		)    Barrel drums    Hourglass or waisted drums    Goblet or chalice drums    Kettle, pot or vessel drums    Frame drums		(possibly a sub of conical/barrel)    Friction drums    Mirlitonswhat to do with string drums etc.
name: membranophone

disambiguation: generic member of the viol family, use for "viol" credits
description: The generic member of the viol family, use it for "Viol" credits, most viola da gamba credits are however the bass viol.
name: viola da gamba

description: The ukulele is a small guitar-like instrument commonly associated with Hawaiian music. It generally has four nylon or gut strings.
name: ukulele

disambiguation: Middle-Low member of the saxophone family
description: The most common of the lower members of the saxophone family, it is the middle-low baritone.
name: baritone saxophone

description: The bagpipe is an instrument consisting of a series of enclosed reeds fed by a bag of air.
name: bagpipe

description:
Family of end-blown woodwind flutes with a thumb-hole and seven finger-holes, it is the most common flute in Western classical tradition.
The family consists of a wide assortment of sizes:
  • garklein recorder
  • sopranino recorder
  • soprano recorder (descant)
  • alto recorder (treble)
  • tenor recorder
  • bass recorder
  • great bass recorder (c-bass)
  • contrabass recorder
  • subcontrabass recorder

Not to be confused with the transverse (side-blown) Western concert flute.
annotation:
Family of end-blown Woodwind flutes, these are flutes with a whistle mouthpiece aka fipple. Specifically, recorders have a thumb-hole and seven finger-holes, it is the most common flute in western classical tradition.

The Family consists of a wide assortment of sizes, the most common being soprano, alt, tenor and bass;

* garklein recorder
* sopranino recorder
* soprano recorder (descant)
* alto recorder (treble)
* tenor recorder
* bass recorder
* great bass recorder (c-bass)
* contrabass recorder
* subcontrabass recorder

Not to be confused with the transverse (side-blown) Western concert flute.
From about 1673 to about 1695 the names ''flute'' and ''recorder'' overlapped, but from 1673 to the late 1720s the word ''flute'' always meant this end-blown instrument. In the 1720s the transverse flute however became so popular that the convention from Europe of distinguishing the instruments was copied into English, thus the end-blown now became known as common flute, English flute and similar, while the transverse became known as the German flute or just flute. despite this, even until 1765 some writers meant the end blown variant when writing "flute".
name: recorder

description: The biwa is a short-necked Japanese fretted lute which is played with a large triangular-shaped plectrum.
name: biwa

disambiguation: Small bass of modern violin family
description: Also know as violoncello (the "small large viol"), it is the medium bass member of the modern violin family and a principal member of the symphony orchestra.
name: cello

description:
It is known by many names, based on the full "alto de viola da braccio": "alto", "bratsch (braccio)", "viola", etc.
It is the alto member of the modern violin family and a principal member of the symphony orchestra.
name: viola

description: Oboe (soprano)
name: oboe

description: The ocarina is a type of vessel flute which has a mouthpiece extending from the body.
name: ocarina

description: The mbira or kalimba (also known by many other names) is an African thumb piano.
name: mbira

description: Natural brass instruments only play notes in the instrument's harmonic series.
name: natural brass instruments

description: The koto is a traditional Japanese string instrument with 13 strings that are strung over 13 movable bridges along the width of the instrument.
name: koto

disambiguation: Commonly used bellowed free reed with keys/buttons
description: Invented and developed by several people in the early 1800's, it has an arm operated bellows with keys or buttons at one end and bass buttons at the other.
name: accordion

description: Soundbox made of gourd, it has 18-21 (6-7 on frets and 11-15 sympathetic under the frets) metal strings, two bridges and a long wooden neck where the tuning pegs of the sympathetic strings are attached. Used in India since ancient times, it flourished during the 16-17th before arriving at it's current form in the 18th century. It became popular worldwide in the 1950-60.
name: sitar

description:
Not to be confused with melophone, a bellowed free reed shaped like a lute.
Originating in the 19th century horn-design boom, it is used mostly in outside concert and marching music.
name: mellophone

description: Named after the Greek god Pan, they are a selection of end-blown pipes made of reeds, bamboo, wood or similar. Many different variations exists around the world, especially in South America.
name: pan flute

description: The sheng is a Chinese free reed instrument consisting of a number of vertical pipes.
name: sheng

description: Bass is a common but generic credit which refers to more than one instrument, the most common being the bass guitar and the double bass (a.k.a. contrabass, acoustic upright bass, wood bass). Please use the correct instrument if you know which one is intended.
name: bass

description: Popular as a musical education tool, it is usually made of plastic with a keyboard, its free-reed mouthpiece can also have an optional air tube. It has many brand names.
name: melodica

description: Known also as contrabass or upright bass, it is the largest and lowest-pitched member of the modern violin family and a principal member of the symphony orchestra.
name: double bass

disambiguation: Folk drone zither from N. America
description: Historically a folk instrument from Appalachia, its elongated figure-of-eight shaped soundbox is made of various woods and often has heart-shaped sound-holes. It has 3 to 4 metal strings (including drone) and is fretted diatonically.
name: Appalachian dulcimer

disambiguation: Set of drums in modern music
description: Set of drums developed from the 1930's onward, it is used in Jazz, Swing, Rock and Pop music. It consists of snare drum, tom-toms, hi-hats, cymbals and bass drum.
name: drums (drum set)

description: The geomungo is a traditional Korean zither, based on the Chinese guqin, which typically has 6 strings.
name: geomungo

description: Solid body 4-stringed electric bass guitar. The most common for "bass guitar" and "bass" credits in popular (rock) music.
name: electric bass guitar

description: Used especially in blues, American folk and country, it consists of a rectangle shape with soundholes along the wide side, where air is blown and drawn across free reeds which are mounted on a plate inside.
name: harmonica

description: Consisting of a stick, a string and an resonator of various materials, it is used in many countries' low-cost and DIY cultures. It's technically a variable tension chordophone.
name: washtub bass

description: Plucked by the mouth, it consists of a characteristically shaped frame with a metal or bamboo reed (tine). There are many variants around the world.
name: mouth harp

description: Also known as Spanish guitar, it is used in classical, folk and other styles, the strings are nylon or gut.

description: Please help move wrongly credited relationships from this, most if not almost all should probably just be "guitar" with credit (guitars).
name: guitar family

description: While also known as English horn, it is neither a horn nor English, but a transposing member of the oboe family, pitched at F.

description: The harp is a plucked string instrument consisting of multiple strings stretched across a vertical frame.
name: harp

description: This is the specific instrument, for other, "lute-like" instruments, see lute family.
name: lute

description: Very wide grouping, played by hitting directly aka idiophones and membranophones (from drums to xylophones). Use the closest approximate instrument possible for credits, use percussion with a credit if no better can be found and create an instrument ticket if necessary.
name: percussion

description: The nose flute is a flute played by the nose commonly found in countries in and around the Pacific.
name: nose flute

description: Typical metal ribbed tool used for washing, still in it's wooden frame, often has is additional noisemakers attached, such as cowbell or woodblock. It is played with thimbles as plectrum.
name: washboard

description: Similar to how a piano works, here keys operate hammers that strike metal plates, creating a soft bell sound.
name: celesta

description: Larger orchestral version of chimes, closed top hollow metal tubes are set in a stand with a damper operated by pedals, they are tuned at a definite pitch and played with mallets.
name: tubular bells

disambiguation: Arrangement of struck tuned wooden bars.
name: xylophone

description: Also known as swanee whistle or piston flute, it consists of a mouthpiece similar to the one of a recorder and a tube with a piston that varies the pitch. It is often used as a sound effect.
name: slide whistle

description:
Popular from 1500 to 1650, also known as zink, it was octagonal with seven holes like flute but mouthpiece like trumpet.
For the modern brass instrument, see cornet.
name: cornett

description:
For the accordion also known as Melodeon, see diatonic button accordion.
For the mouth blown keyed MELODION, see melodica.
For the portable reed organ used in India see harmonium.
Also known as pump organ, it is large, looks like an upright piano and has pedals attached to bellows with reeds. Sound is produced by playing the keyboard.
name: reed organ

description:
Common and popular metallophone, usually an arrangement of metal keys or slabs on a wooden resonator box.
For the instrument often used in bell towers, see carillon.
For the instrument called orchestra bell/chime in some languages, see tubular bells.
name: glockenspiel

description: Homemade combination of a wooden pole with beer bottle tops and other jingles and a hefty boot at the bottom to create thumping bass, it is often decorated with hats, hair or stuffed animals.

name: monkey stick

description: These have holes along the body and sound production is similarly to woodwinds.

description: Simple six-holed fipple flute, originally made of metal; it used to cost a penny, giving it the alternate name “penny whistle”.

description: Pair of concave wood, bone, shell or even fibreglass shells, they are combined by a string and are often used by dancers.

description: The lasso d'amore, whirly tube or corrugaphone is a corrugated plastic tube which is spun in a circle.

description: It is based on the Chinese sheng, but is smaller.

description: Timpani (Kettle drum)

disambiguation: Alto or vertical violin, for French "alto" credits, choose viola

description: Bass member of the guitar family. For the electric variant use electric bass guitar for the acoustic one, use acoustic bass guitar.

description: Used in turntablism, vinyl records are not simply played on it, instead DJ's perform creating sound.

name: bowed string instruments

description: Other instruments. If you can't find an instrument, please request it.

description:
Set of many bronze bells, often mechanized and operated by keyboard, they are set in the bell tower (belfry) of important buildings.

description: conch shell

description: Metal bell used in various genres, it is often attached to a drum kit.

Not to be confused with European upright reed organ also commonly known as "Harmonium".
Also known as the samvadini, it was developed in India from imported reed organs. Consists of a wooden box-shape with a keyboard and a bellows in the back; both are operated by the same player, often a singer. While upright versions exist, they are rare.

description: Madal, hand drum originating from Nepal

description: Used in the traditional music of Vietnam, it is made of wood with a gourdshaped bell.

description: The banhu is a Chinese bowed string instrument in the huqin family. It is also called banghu for its use in bangzi opera.

description: Open in one end, it has a strap to hold while ringing.

description: Long necked bowl lute, it is named after a related Turkish lute.

description: Taking the concept of musical glasses but mounting the incrementing bowls on a turnable spindle, it is played with damp fingers.

description: The zhonghu is a Chinese bowed string instrument developed from the erhu and tuned a fourth or a fifth lower.

description: The sanshin is an Okinawan string instrument which consists of a snakeskin-covered body, neck and three strings. It is traditionally played with a plectrum made of horn worn on the index finger.

description: Santur, Middle Eastern

description: Made of wood, its soundbox is oblong and its neck is short.

description: An electric derivation of the sitar, it often features sympathetic strings and a more guitar shaped body.

description: Ancient hammered dulcimer with trapezoid walnut or maple soundbox, 25 bridges each with 4 strings that are hit by special mallets called mezrab. Used in traditional, folk and mystic Sufi music.

description: The sênh tiền is a Vietnamese instrument which is a combination of clappers, a rasp and a jingle, made from three pieces of wood with old Chinese coins attached.

description: The nyckelharpa is a traditional Swedish string instrument.

description: Kanun, Arabic plucked strings

description: The gaohu is a Chinese bowed string instrument developed from the erhu and tuned a fourth higher.

description: The dahu, also known as cizhonghu or xiaodihu, is a large Chinese bowed string instrument in the huqin family.

annotation: Lute Family:* resonating body* a neck* the strings run along the neck and can be stopped at different pitches* ex: guitar, bass guitar, mandolin, banjo, balalaika, sitar, pipaZither family* does not have a neck* the strings are stretched across the soundboard* ex: autoharp, kantele, gusli, kannel, kankles, kokles, koto, guqin, gu zhengHarp family:* strings are perpendicular to the soundboard and do not run across it.* ex: concert harp, lyreThe harpsichord is also a plucked string instrument, despite not fitting into any of these categories, because its strings are struck or plucked by the plectrum attached to the keys.The harpsichord, taishogoto, nolin and bulbultarang are all ''keyed plucked'' string instruments.* yoke lute family?contains such as the lyra (but many are lutes misnamed (eg byzantine))unsure how differs from harp now.our Harp and Zither are a pain in the ass and should probably instead by renamed "-family" - but we all know what will happen if I do that :|so they'll just have to become crap generic instruments and have everything moved out of them instead.
name: plucked string instruments

description: Family of Hmông flutes.
name: hmông flute

description: The gehu is a Chinese bowed string instrument, with four strings and tuned like the cello.
name: gehu

description: Named after the myth of the nymph Syrinx, this reed pan flute was used in ancient Greece.
name: syrinx

description: The kèn lá is an instrument used by the Hmong minority of Vietnam which consists of a leaf which is curled up and positioned in the mouth so it vibrates when it is blown.
name: kèn lá

description: Ede traditional flute, four finger holes, blowing reed.
name: đing buốt

description: The diyingehu is a Chinese bowed string instrument, with four strings and tuned like the double bass.
name: diyingehu

description: It has a short fretted neck originally with four silk but now usually nylon or steel strings, and large flat round body, earning it the nickname "moon lute".

description: The đàn tranh is a a long Vietnamese zither with sixteen strings and high, movable bridges. The strings are plucked with plectrums, while the left hand is used for ornamenting the notes by pressing the strings.
name: đàn tranh

description: A variant of the Hmông flute, in which the flute blower’s lips enclose the blowing hole with the vibrating free reed inside.

description: Goblet drums are single-headed drums with a goblet shaped body.

description: A latter-day construction in the form of a four-stringed, square-bodied bass guitar.
name: đàn tứ dây

description: Tuned a fourth above and about three quarters the size of a standard violin.

description: The đàn tỳ bà is a four-stringed Vietnamese lute with a pear-shaped body. Like the Chinese pipa from which is derived, it has greatly elevated frets at the neck.

description: Simple, single-toned and round-bodied whistle often used for regulation and signalling (sport, traffic, ...).
name: whistle

description: Although similar to and introduced at the same time as the shamisen, it is unique to japan. With ebony neck and coconut body its three (rarely four) strings are played upright with a horsetail bow.
name: kokyu

description: Cow horns without fingerholes, with mouthpiece and free reed.
name: ki pah

description: Highly stylised wooden block-bell, it is used in religious ritual. Its prototype, fish board (gyoban) is more obviously shaped like a fish.
name: wooden fish

description: Played by manipulating the airstream through bamboo pipes using cupping and clapping, this Vietnamesian "Air Xylophone" was traditionally played in the rice-field.
annotation: The k'lông pút is an instrument from the central highlands of Vietnam played by ethnic groups such as the Xơ Đăng and the Bahnar. It consists of a number of different sized bamboo tubes laid horizontally which are played by the musician clapping their slightly cupped hands in front of the tubes in order to push air into the tubes.
name: k'lông pút

description:
"Rebab" (and other variant spellings) is the name for chiefly these 3 types of bowed/plucked string instrument families:
  • Large, short necked boatshaped "sarinda" type, here the kabuli rebab.
  • Small, long necked spike fiddle "huqyin" type, here the Indonesian rebab.
  • various sizes, varying necklength, pearshaped "Cretan lyra" type, here the bowed lutes proper.


Given the name cross-overs they are confused with eachother in most sources. Curiously, this cross-over confusion extends to related but separately or similarly named instruments as well, for example Ghijak (a spikefiddle) and Ghaychak (a boat-shaped).
It is, for the meantime, unknown how, if at all, these 3 subtypes are related.

For the spike fiddle used in gamelan, see Indonesian rebab.
For the plucked, boat-shaped Afghani instrument also know as kabuli rabab, see rubab.
For the medieval Indian plucked lute see Seni rebab.
For the medieval European pear-shaped fiddle see rebec.
name: rebab

description: The sanxian is a Chinese lute with three strings.
name: sanxian

description: Important to the Mongolians, it is trapezoid shaped with two traditionally horsehair, now often nylon, strings fastened by wooden pegs at the end which is carved like a horse head.
name: morin khuur

description: The song loan is a traditional Vietnamese instrument consisting of a hollow wooden body (about 7 cm in diameter) attached to a flexible spring with a wooden ball on the other end and played with the foot.

disambiguation: Smallest member of the new violin family
description: Tuned an octave above and about quarter the size of the traditional violin.

description: Phách are small wooden sticks beaten on a small piece of bamboo or a wooden block. The sound produced is used to keep time.

description: Used traditionally since 16th-17th century by lǎutari, it is made of bamboo or reed stopped with cork and beeswax set in a curved bottom bar.

description: It is related to similar hammered dulcimers in India, middle east and Europe.

disambiguation: Beijing opera upmost small & high pitch huqin
description: The jinghu is a Chinese bowed string instrument with two strings used primarily in Beijing opera.

description: The trống bông is a wooden Vietnamese drum with a single drumhead which is played with both hands.

description: Chinese family of bowed spike-fiddles, usually with 2, occasionally 3-4 strings, the bodies made of wood and covered with skin occasionally thin wood or made of coconut.

description: Bendir, frame drum from North Africa, doesn't have jingles.
name: bendir

description: Gankogui, iron bell
name: gankogui

description:
Do not confuse with:
  • Serbo-Croat “tamburica” ensemble.
  • Persian/Turkish ancient things that evolved from “tanbur”.
  • Unrelated Indian drone “tanpura”.
  • Related Indian “pandour”.
name: tambura

description: Pí thiu or Pí khui vertical flute
name: pí thiu

description: The tiêu is a Vietnamese end-blown flute related to the Chinese xiao.
name: tiêu

description: Western concert flute is the most common variant of the flute and is commonly referred to as just "flute".
name: concert flute

description:
For the organ also known as Melodeon, see reed organ.
For the mouth blown keyed MELODION, see melodica.
Also known as Melodeon, it has 1 to 2 rows of buttons that each produce two tones (bisonoric).
name: diatonic button accordion

description: The duduk is a traditional Armenian double reed woodwind instrument.
name: duduk

description: Played ceremonially by Igbo people, it is a clay jug beaten with hands to create sounds.
name: udu

description: trắng jâu bass form of trắng lu
name: trắng jâu

description:
Gamelan is basically split up in 3 traditions: the Balinese, the Sundanese and the Javanese, with each area having several different gamelan ensembles from large to small, each including a variety of instruments.
Most if not all gamelan instruments come in two scales, Sléndro and Pélog, these are tuned differently and large gamelan orchestras always include at-least one of each scale and often several sets in each.
Gamelan is an integrated part of Indonesian culture, is used in important traditions and throughout Indonesian life.
name: gamelan

description: Developed as an extended range bass-lute in Italy during the late sixteenth century, it has an extended neck with a second pegbox.
name: theorbo

description: Initially developed in 1880's by Gütter, it was produced and sold by Zimmerman in America and became popular in the 1910 and onward. Wooden box zither has spring mounted bars used to mute strings for chords.
name: autoharp

description: The đing năm is a gourd mouth organ used by minority ethnic groups in the central highlands of Vietnam.
name: đing năm

description: The binzasara is a Japanese percussion instrument made of many small slats of wood connected by a spine of string with handles at each end.
name: bin-sasara

description: Created by Zeynel Abidin Cümbüş, who named himself after it, it’s a banjolin-like modern Turkish instrument.
name: cümbüş

description: Larger and deeper than the tin whistle, it was developed by Overton and made of aluminium.
name: low whistle

description: Made of hollowed out wood or bamboo, it has incisions or slits as soundholes. Slit drums are among the most ancient and earliest instruments.
name: slit drum

description: Tube made of metal or bamboo, it is filled with seeds, pebbles or sand. Especially used in Latin American music, it is shaken rhythmically to produce sound.
name: shakers

description:
Used in sacred rituals, it is made of metal or clay rattle with metal discs which jangle when shook.
Not to be confused with the West African calabash sistrum or disc rattle (n'goso m'bara).
name: sistrum

description: Chinese pear-shaped plucked lute with four strings and 12 to 26 frets.
name: pipa

description: The banjitar is a six-string banjo with the neck of a guitar.
name: banjitar

description: Dispenses with the frame altogether, and is worn as a vest, it is played with spoons or bottle openers.
name: frottoir

description: The surdo is a large bass drum used in Brazilian music, most notably samba.
name: surdo

description: Tanbou ka or Tambu ka (a small high-pitched drum).
name: tanbou ka

disambiguation: Arrangement of struck tuned metal bars.
description: Consisting of tuned metal bars, slates or keys struck with mallets and arranged (often on resonators of sonorous material) in various scales. Compare xylophone for the wooden bar equivalent.
name: metallophone

description: The riq is a type of tambourine used as a traditional instrument in Arabic music.
name: riq

description: The daf is a large Persian frame drum used in popular and classical music. The frame is usually made of hardwood with many metal ringlets attached and the membrane is usually goatskin.
name: daf

description: The alto flute is a concert flute in G, lower in tone than the flûte d'amour.
name: alto flute

description: Dobro, resonator guitar
name: resonator guitar

description: The bass flute is a flute, pitched one octave below the C concert flute, with a tube about 1.5 meters long.
name: bass flute

description: Chacha, west Indian rattle
name: chacha

description: Used for more than 250 years, its one chanter and usually four drones have narrow bores.
name: Northumbrian pipes

description: Japanese traditional drum beaten with sticks called bachi.
name: taiko

description: German/Bohemian harp
name: German harp

description: The zarb is a goblet drum from Persia.
name: zarb

description:
Not to be confused with the 17-18 century French court oboe cromorne.
Used during the Renaissance, its double-reed is inside a windcap and its body ends in a decorative curve.
annotation:
NOTE! Likely anything credited as "cromorne" that's FRENCH is WRONG, because it's called "tournebout" in French!

there is a separate French instrument called cromorne: https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cromorne
For now, use oboe or double-reed on these.
name: crumhorn

description: The đàn tam is a three-stringed fretless lute from Vietnam.
name: đàn tam

description: saó ôi (flute of the Muong)
name: sáo meò

description: The dohol is a large cylindrical drum used in Iran and Afghanistan.
name: dohol

description: Percussion instrument from Martinique made of a piece of bamboo laid horizontally and beaten with sticks.
name: ti bwa

description: The khèn Mèo is a mouth organ used by the Hmong people. It has bamboo pipes (typically six) which each have a free reed.
name: khèn Mèo

description: A pipe organ, such as the Wurlitzer, meant to accompany early films.
name: theatre organ

description: A “slide whistle”-like type of Hmông flute.
name: pang gu ly hu hmông

description: Southern Ugandan giant xylophone, made on with resonating hardwood bars.
name: amadinda

disambiguation: 12th century to present double reed woodwind
description:
Not to be confused with zummara or other double clarinets with similar names.
For the multiple bore free reed created in 1880, see Martinshorn.
For the similarly named single-reed woodwind, see chalumeau.
For the Japanese descendant named from Portuguese, see charumera.
For the Catalan shawm, see tible.
For the Italian ciaramella, see piffero.
For the bagpipe, see xeremies.

European medieval and Renaissance conical bore double-reed woodwind, two types evolved; one from Middle-Eastern instruments and one from bagpipe chanters. A combination of both were used to develop the modern oboe.
name: shawm

description: West African xylophone that uses gourds as its resonators.
name: balafon

description: Large box lute-zither with a short, unfretted neck. It has 30 or more strings fanned out on the body, the four to eight bass strings are strung to the neck.
name: bandura

description: The darbuka is an hourglass-shaped goblet drum from Greece, the Middle East and India.
annotation:
seems the darbuka and the dumbek are (somewhat) different instruments: https://tickets.metabrainz.org/browse/INST-69?focusedId=72231&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels:comment-tabpanel#comment-72231
more research is needed, for now please use instrument credits!
name: darbuka

description: The Vietnamese guitar is similar to a normal guitar, but with scalloped fingerboard resulting in elevated frets similar to the đàn nguyệt.
name: Vietnamese guitar

description: Davul, turkish drum
name: davul

description: Classical North Indian hand drum.
name: dholak

description: West African gourd-shaker, a net of beads covers it.
name: shekere

description: Made of bone or wood, these are paired sticks of sonorous material used in folk music.
name: bones

disambiguation: Single pitch bamboo rattle xylophone used in Sundanese gamelan
description: Usually consisting of 2-3 carved bamboo tubes suspended in a wooden or bamboo frame that is shook. It has been in use since ancient times by Sundanese peoples.
name: angklung

description: Cajón, Peruvian box drum
name: cajón

description: The flûte d'amour is the mezzo-soprano instrument of the flute family.
name: flûte d'amour

description: The ding tac ta is a free reed wind instrument played by the Ê Đê minority in Vietnam. It is made of a bamboo tube with three holes and a gourd wind chamber.
annotation:
hard to find anything about this. initially entered it as dinh tăktàr

have found names Đinh Tăk Tar, Đinh Takta, đing tak ta, đing buốt klé, Đing Buốt

according to https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rade_people#Music it's "đing tak ta (or đing buốt klé)"
and this brings to https://www.vienamnhac.vn/vietnamese-music-space/museum/musical-instruments/%C4%91ing-buot---airophone

vietnamese page for the people there https://vi.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ng%C6%B0%E1%BB%9Di_%C3%8A%C4%91%C3%AA#V%C4%83n_h%C3%B3a has the link as "Đĭng atŭt|Đĭng Buôt" which suggests "Đĭng atŭt" as an alias too. however not found anything after a cursory search.
name: ding tac ta

description: Lute played by Gnawa people, its camel hide covered wooden soundbox has 3 goat gut strings.
name: gumbri

description: An Irish/Scottish harp.
name: Irish harp / clàrsach

disambiguation: Arrangement of hanging struck tuned metal rods.
description:
Bar or pole shaped chimes, usually arranged in a line or circle, hanging free or struck with mallets.
For the instrument often used in bell towers, see carillon.
For the instrument used in orchestra, see tubular bells.
name: chimes

description: The tar is a long-necked, waisted lute found in Azerbaijan, Iran, Armenia, Georgia, and other areas near the Caucasus region. Not to be confused with the drum of the same name.
name: tar

description: The bawu is a Chinese wind instrument. Although shaped like a flute, it is actually a free reed instrument, with a single metal reed. It is played in a transverse (horizontal) manner.
name: bawu

description: Ancient Russian psaltery/box-zither with 4 to 36 metal strings, it is played in a few different ways, depending on the variation (see annotation). Originally similar to a flat harp, it was played at ceremonies and other festivities.
annotation: Various versions of the gusli is as follows:Shlemovidnye or "Helmet-shaped" this is played horizontally on the lap. It is common in the southern and western regions of Kievan Rus'.Krylovidnye or "Wing-shaped" this resembles the other Baltic-psalteries the most, it is played like the modern guitar. it was perfected by O.U. Smolensky and N.I. Prilav in 1900. It is common in the northern parts, especially Novgorod and Pskov.Claviroobraznie or the "Clavichord" variant was invented 1914 by N.P. Fomin. it has a keyboard which enacted dampeners on the strings, thereby enabling things like glissandi and arpeggios, it is used primarily in Russian folk instrument orchestras.
name: gusli

description: The shruti box is similar to a harmonium and is used to provide a drone accompaniment.
name: shruti box

description: Ancient Chinese vertical, end-blown flute made of bamboo.
name: xiao

description: Invented in 16th century England, it had low-tension metal strings and sloping frets.
name: orpharion

description: The daegeum is a large transverse flute from Korea which is made of bamboo.
name: daegeum

description: Traditional and mythological psaltery of Finland, it comes in two versions; the oldest, a one piece bridge-less psaltery with 5 to 20 originally horsehair, later metal, strings and a modern "Concert" box-zither variant with a switch mechanism to alter the up to 40 strings sharps and flats.
name: kantele

description: Oboe d'amore / Oboe d'amour (mezzo-soprano)
name: oboe d'amore

disambiguation: Second lowest member of the saxophone family
description: Second largest and lowest member of the saxophone family. It is similar to the baritone, but larger and with a longer loop near the mouthpiece.
name: bass saxophone

description: Originating in Africa, it is used in carnivals and samba music. Consisting of a wooden or metal barrel, its single membrane has a tuning-stick attached.
name: cuíca

description: A class of South-American guitars.
name: cuatro

description: A tom-tom (or just tom) is a cylindrical drum with no snare, commonly found in a standard drum set.
name: tom-tom

description: A talkbox is an effects device which enables a musician to modify the sound of an instrument.
name: talkbox

description: A hi-hat is a typical part of a drum kit, consisting of a pair of cymbals mounted on a stand.
name: hi-hat

description:
It differs from other chimes by addition of pendulum(s), such to be worked by wind, the sonorous parts can be rods, bells or other shapes of metal, wood, glass or ceramic.
Often decorated, it is seen as a good luck charm.
name: wind chime

description:
For the French bagpipe, see cornemuse du centre.
For Italian cornamusa, see bagpipe.
Related to the crumhorn, it was used in the Renaissance. Because only a paragraph by Praetorius is the only known information, all reconstructions are approximations.
name: cornamuse

description: The bass harmonica is a type of octave harmonica where the lowest note (E) is the same as that on a bass guitar.
name: bass harmonica

description: The janggu or janggo is a double-headed hourglass shaped drum which is the most widely used drum used in the traditional music of Korea.
name: janggu

description: A piano whose strings are bowed, using nylon filament or other materials.
name: bowed piano

description: Used by the Quechua and Aymara, it is a small lute of 5 courses with 10 strings.
name: charango

description: The taragot is a Turkish/Hungarian/Romanian reed instrument related to the saxophone and clarinet.
name: taragot

disambiguation: Contra/double-bass member of the viol family
description: Violone, The largest/deepest member of the Viol family.
name: violone

description: The kkwaenggwari is a small flat brass gong, typically about 20cm in diameter, which is used primarily in the folk music of Korea.
name: kkwaenggwari

description: The virginal is a smaller and simpler rectangular form of the harpsichord with only one string per note.
name: virginal

description: The Wurlitzer electric piano is an electric piano where flat steel reeds are struck by felt hammers.
name: Wurlitzer electric piano

description:
Not to be confused with the Spanish double-reed dulzaina.
Used in the renaissance, it is made of maple wood with a folded bore and conical bell.
name: dulcian

description: A bell tree is a percussion instrument, consisting of vertically nested inverted metal bowls.
name: bell tree

description: The spilåpipa is a Swedish fipple flute with eight finger-holes on the top, but no thumb-holes. It has a modal tuning.
name: spilåpipa

description: Small, high-pitched, transverse flute, similar to the piccolo, but with a narrower bore.
name: fife

description: Slightly smaller, four-string version of the steel-string acoustic guitar.
name: tenor guitar

description: Looks like a recorder, but with double reeds and bagpipe fingering system. Mostly used to learn how to play the pipes, but are occasionally played in their own right.
name: practice chanter

description: The caxixi is a shaker originating in Brazil which is made of a small wicker basket containing seeds or other small particles.
name: caxixi

description: Percussion performed by parts of the body.
name: body percussion

description: The sarangi is a short-necked, bowed string instrument from India, Nepal and Pakistan.
name: sarangi

description: Widely used in Korea, it has a wood soundbox and a rod neck with two silk-strings, heldt on the knee while played with a bow.
name: haegeum

description: The dizi is a Chinese transverse flute typically made of bamboo. In Chinese, it is sometimes just called 笛 (di), but in Japanese 笛 (fue) is a more generic word referring to a whole class of flutes rather than this specific instrument.
name: dizi

disambiguation: Largest member of the saxophone family
description: The largest and lowest pitch member of the saxophone family (ignoring the subcontrabass tubax).
name: contrabass saxophone

description: The kaval is a chromatic end-blown flute from the Balkans and Anatolia.
name: kaval

description: Used in Carnatic tradition, named after goddess of art and music Saraswati, it is known since ancient times. Lute with a gourd sound resonator, it has 24 fixed frets, 7 steel strings (4 main & 3 drone).
name: Saraswati veena

description: A laser harp is an electronic musical instrument consisting of several laser beams to be blocked, in analogy with the plucking of the strings of a harp, in order to produce sounds.
name: laser harp

description: Variety of bass guitars without frets.
name: fretless bass

description: A bass synthesizer is used to create sounds in the bass range.
name: bass synthesizer

description: Percussion performed with feet, such as foot tapping and clogging.
name: foot stomps

description: A barrel organ is a mechanical musical instrument typically operated by a person turning a crank which turns a barrel which has music encoded onto it.
name: barrel organ

description: Although originally built like a cittern, its 6-7 courses of strings were tuned more like a lute.
name: bandora

description: Used in traditional Andean music, it is the smallest of its family
name: quena

description: The valiha is a bamboo tube zither from Madagascar.
name: valiha

description: The algozey is a wooden, beaked double-flute traditionally played by goat herders in the Punjab region of India and Pakistan.
name: algozey

disambiguation: Middle member of the end-blown fipple flute recorder family
description:
Also known as the descant, it is the third smallest and most common member of the modern recorder family.
Traditionally made of various woods, it is today often made of plastic and used to teach children music.
Not to be confused with the side-blown (concerto) soprano flute.
name: soprano recorder

description: Conical bore double-reed musical instrument from Brittany.
name: bombarde

description: Invented initially as the Hang, it is made of two tuned metal convex pans glued together creating an UFO shape.
name: handpan

description: The piri is a Korean double reed instrument made of bamboo, used in both the folk and classical (court) music of Korea. Related to the Chinese guan and Japanese hichiriki.
name: piri

description: The tumbi is a high pitched, single string plucking instrument associated with folk music of Punjab.
name: tumbi

description: The guqin is a plucked seven-string Chinese musical instrument of the zither family.
name: guqin

description: The guzheng or zheng is a Chinese plucked zither, with 18 to 23 or more strings and movable bridges.
name: guzheng

description: The agogô is a single or multiple bell used in samba music with origins in traditional Yoruba music.
name: agogô

description: Instead of a wooden body, it is amplified by a metal horn resonator; its louder and more directional sound made it useful in loud areas.
name: Stroh violin

description: Like (and developed from) the Northumbrian smallpipes, but with Great Highland Bagpipe fingering.
name: Scottish smallpipes

description: The ancient ancestor of many related lute like instruments.
name: tanbur

description: The Cretan lyra is a Greek pear-shaped, three-stringed bowed musical instrument, central to the traditional music of Crete and parts of Greece.
name: Cretan lyra

description: Primarily in the religious rituals of the Yoruba and diaspora, these hourglass shaped drums have membranes on each end. Their names are largest to least: Iyá, Itótele, Okónkolo.
name: Batá drum

description: A prepared piano is a piano that has had its sound altered by placing objects (preparations) between or on the strings or on the hammers or dampers.
name: prepared piano

description: Family of related plucked box-zithers from the Baltic area, each hold a strong traditional significance within their respective communities Members include: * Kantele from Finland * Kannel from Estland * Kanklės from Lithuania * Kokles from Latvia * Gusli from Russia/Belarus Additional members include the Russian Mari-people's Kusle, the Latvian Livonian-people's Kāndla and the Sápmi Harpu.
annotation: Family of related plucked box-zithers from the Baltic area, each hold a strong traditional significance within their respective communitiesMembers include:* Kantele from Finland* Kannel from Estland* Kanklės from Lithuania* Kokles from Latvia* Gusli from Russia/BelarusAdditional members include the Russian Mari-people's ''Kusle'', the Latvian Livonian-people's ''Kāndla'' and the Sápmi ''Harpu''
name: Baltic psalteries

description: EWI (an acronym for electric wind instrument) is the name of Akai's wind controller.
name: EWI

description: From the Indian subcontinent, it is used at marriages, in temples and concerts - made of wood with a double reed and wood/metal flared bell, it has 6-9 holes.
name: shehnai

description: Oldest instrument of Lithuania, it is made of a special tree in a trapezoid shape, it has a metalbar and wooden pegs at each side were 5 to 12 strings are strung.
annotation: Variations are as follows:* North-eastern Aukštaitians: Being the most ancient form it is simply carved of a single piece of wood.* Western Aukštaitians and Samogitians: Larger than the oldest, it has between eight and twelve strings and sometimes has a stylized carved bird or fish tail.* North-western Samogitians and Suvalkians: The version folk concert kanklės are based on, it is the most decorated with carved spiral ornaments.
name: kanklės

description: A type of fretless zither.
name: Marxophone

description: An empty jug (usually made of glass or stoneware) played with the mouth.
name: jug

description: The saz is a long-necked fretted lute.
name: saz

description: A chamber organ is a small pipe organ.
name: chamber organ

description: The nohkan is a high-pitched bamboo transverse flute from Japan.
name: nohkan

description: A koto with 17 rather than 13 strings, sometimes described as a bass koto.
name: 17-string bass koto

description: The mridangam is a double-sided drum from India.
name: mridangam

description:
For the Japanese descendant named from Portuguese, see charumera.
For the medieval double-reed woodwind see shawm.
Predecessor of the modern clarinet, 7-regular 1-thumb holed single-reed woodwind was in use during baroque and classical era.
name: chalumeau

disambiguation: Ancient large North Indian tube zither
description: Considered the originator of all Indian strings (veena) it was used for ritual and meditation, North Indian raga and Dhrupad music. It has two dried gourd resonators and a body of bamboo with 24 wooden frets and 4 main, 2-3 secondary and one drone string.
name: rudra veena

description: Used in Hindustani dhrupad, this two-headed barrel-drum is tuned like its descendant the tabla.
name: pakhawaj

description: The domra is a long-necked Russian string instrument of the lute family with a round body and three or four metal strings.
name: domra

description: The archlute is a European plucked string instrument developed around 1600 as a compromise between the very large theorbo and the Renaissance tenor lute.
name: archlute

description: The launeddas is a typical Sardinian woodwind instrument, consisting of three pipes.
name: launeddas

description: Known since ancient times in south-east Europe and Turkey, small bronze finger cymbals are used for dancing and other performances. These are similar to the jingles set in some frame drums.
name: zill

description: The atarigane is a Japanese gong which is struck using a deer horn mallet.
name: atarigane

description: Tuned an octave below the traditional violin and at about half the size of the cello, it has a range between the cello and the viola. It has a longer neck and thinner ribs than the cello.
name: tenor violin

description: The dilruba is a bowed string instrument from Northern India, mostly used in religious music and light classical songs.
name: dilruba

description: The khong wong lek is a gong circle used in Thai classical music. It has 18 tuned bossed gongs and is smaller and higher in pitch than the khong wong yai.
name: khong wong lek

description: Name also used in general for reed pipes from the 16th century, it has a conical bore and a windcap.
name: rauschpfeife

description: The khong wong is a gong circle consisting of a number of gongs in a horizontal circular rattan frame. The player sits in the middle.
name: khong wong

description: The thon is a goblet drum with a ceramic or wooden body used in classical Thai and Cambodian music which forms one part of thon and rammana.
name: thon

description: Acoustic guitar without frets.
name: acoustic fretless guitar

description: Simultaneously a woodwind and membranophone, sound is produced by singing or speaking into a thin buzzing membrane.
name: mirliton

description: Used in gagaku, it is a transverse flute.
name: ryuteki

description: The talharpa is a four-stringed bowed lyre from northern Europe, mostly played in Estonia.
name: talharpa

description: Small Portuguese lute with four wire or gut strings, it has many descendants in South and Latin America.
name: cavaquinho

description: The limbe is a Mongolian transverse flute.
name: limbe

description:
Made of bamboo with one end covered with grease-paper, it is a "side-blown" mirliton.
Not to be confused with the Egyptian/Iraqi zummara which is an instrument similar to a chalumeau.
annotation: https://vassallohistory.wordpress.com/2571-2/https://hwawarfjuri.wordpress.com/tag/zummara/https://duckduckgo.com/?q=musical+instruments+of+malta&t=ffab&atb=v166-6&iax=images&ia=images&iai=http%3A%2F%2Fvassallohistory.files.wordpress.com%2F2013%2F04%2Fzummara.jpg
name: żummara

description: The samba whistle is a tri-tone whistle used in samba music and other Brazilian music styles.
name: samba whistle

description: The đàn tứ or đàn đoản is a traditional Vietnamese moon-shaped lute with a short neck.
name: đàn tứ

description: The E♭ clarinet is a member of the clarinet family.
name: E-flat clarinet

description: Possibly dating back as far as 6000 BC, it is a national symbol of the Kyrgyz. Made of a single piece of apricot or juniper wood with 3 gut stings, it has derivations in much of eastern Europe.
name: komuz

description: The most common and based on the original design, its fifth string is shorter than the others, creating an uneven pitch progression.
name: five-string banjo

description: The pedal piano is a kind of piano that includes a pedalboard, enabling bass register notes to be played with the feet, as is standard on the organ.
name: pedal piano

description: The shime-daiko is a small Japanese drum with a short but wide body which has a higher pitch than a normal taiko.
name: shime-daiko

description:
Part of the Sundanese gamelan, these consist of a decorated wood resonator (rancak) upon which is resting six to nine thick, smooth, bronze or iron keys that are hit with mallets of hard wood or buffalo horn.

The saron family consists of the smallest member; saron panerus, the middle pitch member; saron barung and the largest member; sarong demung. Additionally, the largely obsolete slentho (which has been subsumed by the slenthem) is even deeper than the demung and the saron peking, which is a special slendro variant is even higher than the panerus, of which it shares an overlapping range. Finally the saron wayang is used in wayang performances.
annotation: lowest pitch to highestslentho it has basically been replaced by slenthem.sarong demung 90 cmsarung barung 75 cm (rincik)sarong panerus 60 cm (peking)
name: saron family

description: Traditional instrument from Laos, it is also used in Thailand and even Vietnam. it consists of 14 bamboo pipes with a small hollowed hardwood soundbox.
name: khene

disambiguation: Large North Indian fretless sliding tube zither
description: Played like a slide guitar, it has two large gourd resonators with a teak body that often ends in carved peacock heads. Fretless, it has 4 main, 5 chikari and 13 resonance strings, slide is a glass orb named batta.
name: vichitra veena

description: The nagadou-daiko is an elongated barrel-shaped Japanese drum.
name: nagadou-daiko

description: The Lyricon is an electronic wind instrument.
name: Lyricon

description: Used in classical and orchestral music, mostly by orchestras in Vienna.
name: Wiener Horn

description: The esraj is a bowed string instrument from Eastern and Central India, mostly used as an accompanying instrument.
name: esraj

description: The jing'erhu is a Chinese bowed string instrument, similar to the erhu, so named because is played in Beijing opera.
name: jing'erhu

description: The kartal is an Indian percussion instrument with jingles, played with the hands, mainly used in Kirtans, Bhajans and in Rajastani folk music.
name: kartal

description: The żafżafa or rabbaba is a Maltese friction drum consisting of a container (made of tin, pottery or wood) covered with animal skin with a long Arundo donax reed attached.
name: żafżafa

description: The heike biwa is a biwa with four strings and five frets used to play Heike Monogatari.
name: heike biwa

description: Indian mouth harp, played in Carnatic and Rajastani folk music.
name: morsing

description: Tap dancing is a type of dance in which the dancer wears special shoes that make a clicking sound as the dancer's feet strike the floor.
name: tap dance

description: Hybrid between the viol and the bandora, it has an extra set of plucked strings in addition to the bowed ones. Used regularly in Europe until the end of the 18th century.
name: baryton

description: Computer drives used for producing music, be it hard drives, floppy, CD or other.
name: disk drive

description: The octave mandolin is a fretted string instrument with four pairs of strings tuned in fifths, G, D, A, E (low to high), an octave below a mandolin.
name: octave mandolin

description: Used in gagaku, it is a double reed flute.
name: hichiriki

description: Persian / Turkish / Arabic end-blown flute with five or six finger holes and one thumb hole.
name: ney

description: The dombra is a long-necked lute from central Asia.
name: dombra

description: The satsuma biwa is a biwa with four strings and frets popularised during the Edo period.
name: satsuma biwa

description: Made of cane, it is used in Ecuador.
name: rondador

description: A tar is a single-headed frame drum from North Africa and the Middle East.
name: tar

description: The duxianqin is a one-string zither which is likely derived from the Vietnamese đàn bầu.
name: duxianqin

description: Ching are a pair of small hand cymbals used in Thai and Cambodian music.
name: ching

description: The xiaoluo is a Chinese small flat gong whose pitch rises when struck with the side of a flat wooden stick.
name: xiaoluo

description:
For the Italian bagpipe, see zampogna.
Also known as zampona, traditional Andean panpipe has two rows of pipes tied together with colourful bands.
name: siku

description: Chap are a pair of cymbals used in Thai and Cambodian music. They are larger, flatter and thinner than the cymbals known as ching.
name: chap

description: Maddale is a double-headed drum from Karnataka, India. It is the primary rhythmic accompaniment in Yakshagana.
name: maddale

description: The ranat thum is a xylophone from Thailand consisting of 18 wooden bars suspended by cords over a boat-shaped trough resonator. It is similar to the ranat ek but lower in pitch.
name: ranat thum

description: A larger version of tef, used to indicate the rhythmic structures (usul) in makam music.
name: daire

description: A Turkish version of tambourine / daf, made from animal skin and played with the fingers.
name: tef

description: Chinese cymbals specially used in the Beijing opera.
name: naobo

description: The ōtsuzumi is an hourglass-shaped Japanese drum, larger than the kotsuzumi.
name: ōtsuzumi

description: A mouth organ is a generic term for free reed aerophone with one or more air chambers fitted with a free reed.
name: mouth organ

description: Double headed drum from India.
name: dhol

description: The Reactable is an electronic musical instrument consisting of a round translucent table on which blocks are placed.
name: Reactable

description: Besides being used for writing, it has also been used in percussion.
name: typewriter

description: Bass member of Chinese ruan family of lutes.
name: daruan

disambiguation: synthesizer played like a wind instrument
description: Wind synthesizer or wind controller, it is connected to a MIDI controller and is played like a wind instrument.
name: wind synthesizer

description: Made of a whole animal-skin, it is used in festivals. The blowpipe (mserka) is made of rubber or cane, the chanter (saqqafa) are two cane pipes, one 2 holed, the other 5 holed, with the bell of an ox horn.
name: żaqq

description: Hard disk configured to produce tones in pattern.
name: hard disk drive

description: Important to the folk music in northern China, it has a conical wooden body and seven finger holes.
name: suona

description: Developed from the Japanese taishogoto, it is made of wood, often an integral case. It has two courses of strings; drone and melody strings operated by buttons or keys.
name: bulbul tarang

description: Floppy drives configured to produce tones while reading, using software.
name: floppy disk drive

description: The chikuzen biwa is a biwa with either four strings and frets or five strings and frets popularised during the Meiji period.
name: chikuzen biwa

description: Ruan is a family of Chinese plucked lutes.
name: ruan

description: The saw duang is a two-stringed instrument used in traditional Thai music which has a cylindrical soundbox made of wood and a snakeskin resonator.
name: saw duang

description: Turkish pair of small, hemispherical drums.
name: kudüm

description: The chande is a drum used in the traditional and classical music of South India.
name: chande

description: The khong wong yai is a gong circle used in the music of Thailand. It has 16 tuned bossed gongs and is larger and lower in pitch than the khong wong lek.
name: khong wong yai

description: The tonkori is a plucked string instrument played by the Ainu of northern Japan and Sakhalin.
name: tonkori

description: Electric guitar without frets.
name: electric fretless guitar

description: Developed in the early Taisho period to modernise the ningenkin, it has metal strings and typewriter like keys with a wooden lid over the frets.
name: taishogoto

description: Traditionally made of willow, it has four strings and a small, pear-shaped body. Played with a pick, it has a higher pitch than the pipa.
name: liuqin

description: The yatga is a traditional Mongolian plucked zither, similar to the Chinese guzheng.
name: yatga

description: The buk is a Korean drum. While buk is a generic term for drum, it normally refers to a shallow barrel-shaped drum with a wooden body.
name: buk

description: The qilaut is an Inuit frame drum which has a handle and is made of caribou skin.
name: qilaut

description: The daluo is a Chinese large flat gong whose pitch drops when struck with a padded mallet.
name: daluo

description: The Xaphoon is a keyless chromatic single-reed woodwind instrument.
name: Xaphoon

description: The jing is a large gong used in traditional Korean music.
name: jing

description: The yaylı tanbur is a bowed lute from Turkey derived from the older plucked tanbur.
name: yaylı tanbur

description: The hulusi is a Chinese free reed wind instrument which has three bamboo pipes which pass through a gourd.
name: hulusi

description: The ranat ek is a Thai xylophone which consists of 21 wooden bars suspended by cords over a boat-shaped trough resonator and struck by two mallets.
name: ranat ek

description: The shudraga is a Mongolian fretless lute with three strings.
name: shudraga

description: The fujara is a large folk shepherd's fipple flute originated from central Slovakia.
name: fujara

description: The mandocello is a plucked string instrument of the mandolin family, the equivalent to the cello in the violin family.
name: mandocello

disambiguation: Baroque curved flared bell transposing oboe
description: First referred to in 1722, this transposing double-reed has a curved tube and a flared (brass) bell.
name: oboe da caccia

description: Widely used in folk music, opera and music ensembles, it can be round or cone-shaped with cow/pigskin nailed to the larger convex end which has a small hole (guxin).
name: bangu

description: The kotsuzumi or simply tsuzumi is an hourglass-shaped Japanese drum with cords that can be squeezed or released to increase or decrease the tension of the heads.
name: kotsuzumi

description: Dulzaina specifically from Catalonia.
name: gralla

description: Turkish bowl-shaped kemenche, mainly used in classical Ottoman music.
name: classical kemençe

disambiguation: Brass valveless and keyless ancestor of the modern horn
description: Ancestor of the modern horn, it consists of a coiled tubing with a large flared bell. Bugles, posthorns and hunting horns are all natural horns.
name: natural horn

description: The nose whistle (also known as the Humanatone) is a simple instrument played with the nose. The stream of air is directed over an edge in the instrument and the frequency of the notes produced is controlled by the volume of air.
name: nose whistle

description: Turkish box-shaped kemenche, mainly used for folk music.
name: kemençe of the Black Sea

description: Based on the natural trumpet used in the 1500s to 1700s, this mid 20th century reinvention lacks valves but may have vents.
name: baroque trumpet

description: Used in Laos and Isan traditional music, it is made of bamboo or ku wood, the individual stopped pipes are arranged around a central core using beeswax.
name: wot

description: The saw sam sai is a three-stringed bowed instrument from Thailand.
name: saw sam sai

description: The buzuq is a long-necked fretted lute related to the Greek bouzouki and Turkish saz which is associated with the music of Lebanon and Syria.
name: buzuq

description: The doshpuluur is a long-necked Tuvan lute.
annotation: Hornbostel-Sachs: 321.322
name: doshpuluur

description:
Despite the name, it is not a chime but instead consists of tuned metal bars each on individual resonator boxes.
It is similar to glockenspiel.
For the instrument called bar chimes, see chimes.
name: chime bar

description: The tack piano is a permanently altered version of an ordinary piano, which has tacks or nails placed on the felt-padded hammers of the instrument at the point where the hammers hit the strings, giving the instrument a tinny, more percussive sound.
name: tack piano

description: Struck idiophone are ones where sound comes from striking the instrument and it as a whole vibrates, without the use of strings or membranes. Therefore these are most often made of sonorous material: metal, wood, glass and even stone.
annotation: Hornbostel-Sachs 11There are two types: Concussion idiophone is idiophone where the two pieces are hit together and both vibrate (think clapping).Percussion idiophone is idiophone where one sonorous piece is hit with or against non-sonorous pieces (think slapping).
name: struck idiophone

description: The topshuur is a two-stringed lute from Mongolia and Tuva.
name: topshuur

description: Made of bamboo, it has from 4 to 6 finger-holes and a small wedge-shaped fipple. There are many varieties all around Southeast Asia, it is also used in gamelan.
name: suling

description: Made of a gourd wrapped in a beaded net, it is used in Brazilian afoxé music.
name: afoxé

description: Used in the traditional Korean music daechwita, it consists of a large two headed wooden barrel painted with dragon designs.
name: yonggo

description: The guitalele is a guitar-ukulele hybrid, combining the small size of a guitalele with the six strings of a classical guitar.
name: guitalele

description: The saw u is a Thai bowed string instrument which has a soundbox made from a coconut shell with a cowskin resonator.
name: saw u

description: The ajaeng is a bowed Korean zither with 7 (sometimes 8 or 9) strings.
name: ajaeng

description: The taepyeongso is a Korean double reed wind instrument which has a conical wooden body with a metal mouthpiece and cup-shaped metal bell.
name: taepyeongso

description: The tubax is a modified saxophone which is more compact due to the tubing being folded more times.
annotation: Hornbostel-Sachs: 422.212-71
name: tubax

description: Used as rhythm accompaniment, it has a shorter neck and 17-19 frets.
name: tenor banjo

description: The harp guitar is a guitar-based string instrument with any number of additional unstopped strings which can accommodate individual plucking.
name: harp guitar

description: The repinique is a cylindrical drum from Brazil.
name: repinique

description: Originally made of bamboo or wood, it is now metal with springs and is used in Brazilian music.
name: reco-reco

description: The klong khaek is a double-headed barrel drum from Thailand. The heads are different sizes.
name: klong khaek

description: Baroque string instrument sized between the viola and cello, it typically has five strings.
name: violoncello piccolo

description: The klong song na is a barrel drum from Thailand. It is played with the hands and is used in the piphat ensemble.
name: klong song na

description: Used in fado, it has twelve steel strings, strung in six courses.
name: Portuguese guitar

description: The chakhe is a three stringed crocodile shaped plucked zither from Thailand.
name: chakhe

description: The guitarrón mexicano is a very large and deep-bodied Mexican guitar-like instrument with six strings which is traditionally played in mariachi groups.
name: guitarrón mexicano

description: The xun is a vessel flute from China which has a blowing hole at the top.
name: xun

description: The zabumba is a bass drum from Brazil.
name: zabumba

description: Krakebs are large metal castanet-like instruments which are the primary rhythmic component of Gnawa music.
name: krakebs

description: The bass trumpet is a type of low trumpet similar to the valve trombone.
name: bass trumpet

description: Effects refers to devices which enable a musician to modify the sound of an instrument.
name: effects

description: The Paraguayan harp is a 32-48-string diatonic harp used in Paraguay and Venezuela.
name: Paraguayan harp

description: The alfaia is a Brazilian cylindrical drum.
name: alfaia

description: Lamellophones are a family of musical instruments which have one or more long thin plates - "lamella" or "tongues" - which are fixed at one end and free at the other end. The free end is plucked, causing the plate to vibrate.
annotation: Hornbostel-Sachs: 12
name: lamellaphone

description: The shichepshin is a traditional bowed string instrument of the Circassian peoples.
name: shichepshin

description: The ukeke is a Hawaiian musical bow made of koa wood, 16 to 24 inches long and about 1½ inches wide with two or three strings fastened through and around either end, tuned to an A major triad.
name: ukeke

description: The igil is a Tuvan bowed string instrument with two strings.
name: igil

description: Solid metal (often aluminium) rods hanging on a bar, set at an inharmonic pitch.
name: Mark tree

description: Used chiefly in classical Indian songstyles Khyal and Thumri, it has a trapezoid shape with up to 40 metal strings fastened at both sides by iron pegs with one side having tuning keys.
name: swarmandal

description: The taphon is a traditional barrel drum from Thailand.
name: taphon

description: Friction idiophones are idiophones where the sound is created by the instrument being rubbed.
annotation: Hornbostel-Sachs: 13
name: friction idiophone

description: The lavta is a plucked string instrument from Greece and Turkey.
name: lavta

description: Lacking the short drone string of its predecessor, it is usually played with a plectrum and has 22 frets.
name: four-string banjo

description: The rammana is a frame drum used in classical Thai and Cambodian music which forms one part of thon and rammana.
name: rammana

description: The guitarrón chileno is a Chilean guitar-like plucked string instrument which typically has 25 strings.
name: guitarrón chileno

description: The pocket trumpet is a compact size B♭ trumpet, with the same playing range as the regular trumpet.
name: pocket trumpet

description: The sabar is a drum from Senegal which is normally played with one hand and one stick. The body is an elongated cylinder with tapered ends. The head is made of goatskin and is attached to the body using pegs.
name: sabar

description: Developed as early as the 1500-hundreds and used for mail-carrier signalling, it was coiled (usually just once) and valveless.
name: post horn

description: Used in folk-music, It has ten steel strings in five courses.
name: viola caipira

description: The pātē is a Polynesian slit drum made from a hollowed-out log.
name: pātē

description: The diddley bow is a single-stringed American instrument which is typically homemade. It consists of a single string of baling wire tensioned between two nails on a board over a glass bottle, which is used both as a bridge and as a means to magnify the instrument's sound.
name: diddley bow

description: A cylindrical drum is a straight-sided and generally two-headed drum.
name: cylindrical drum

description: Differs from other lutes in that its string tension is greater thus sounding more like the oud. From ancient Greece, it was used as an accompaniment to Cretan lyra.
name: laouto

description: Dunun is a family of West African cylindrical drums.
name: dunun

description: Member of the xylophone family, it has 5 octaves.
annotation: It is not, as the name would suggest, a hybrid of the xylophone and the marimba
name: xylorimba

description: The marímbula is a plucked box musical instrument from the Caribbean.
name: marímbula

description: The Schwyzerörgeli is a type of diatonic button accordion used in Swiss folk music.
name: Schwyzerörgeli

description: The dramyin is a traditional Himalayan long-necked lute with seven strings.
name: dramyin

description: The arghul is a traditional Egyptian double-pipe, single-reed woodwind instrument.
name: arghul

description: The dutar is a long-necked two-stringed lute found in Iran and Central Asia.
name: dutar

description: Short wooden flute used to imitate the sound of ducks.
name: duck call

description: Ingenious to the Ainu, it is made of bamboo with a string that vibrated creates sound.
name: mukkuri

description: A vessel flute is a type of flute with an enclosed rather than cylindrical body.
name: vessel flute

description: The ģīga is a two-stringed bowed zither found in Latvia.
name: ģīga

description: The pi nai is a type of pi normally used in the piphat ensemble.
name: pi nai

description: Originally used just by blacksmiths, the crisp, clear tone produced was noticed by even early composers. In modern use, it is specifically made for music from tuned metal, sometimes placed in a resonator, and is struck with metal hammers.
name: anvil

description: A tromba marina is a triangular bowed string instrument used in medieval and Renaissance Europe that consists of a body and neck in the shape of a truncated cone resting on a triangular base.
name: tromba marina

description: The šargija is a long necked plucked lute used in the folk music of the Balkans.
name: šargija

description: The chau gong is a large gong made of brass or bronze which is almost flat except for the rim.
name: chau gong

description: Ancient reedless fipple flute made of bamboo.
name: khlui

description: The atabaque is a tall Brazilian hand drum.
name: atabaque

description: The klong yao is a goblet drum from Thailand which is usually decorated with a colourful skirt.
name: klong yao

description: The jouhikko is a traditional, 2 or 3 stringed bowed lyre, from Finland and Karelia.
name: jouhikko

description: The pkhachich is a traditional shaken percussion instrument of the Circassian peoples.
name: pkhachich

description: Derived from the Indian tritantri veena by the Persian poet Amir Khusro sometime in 13th century, it had 3 (now 4) strings and a long neck. It later gave name to the Indian sitar.
name: setar

description: The nyatiti is a five to eight-stringed plucked string instrument from Kenya.
name: nyatiti

description: The chanzy is a three-stringed Tuvan lute.
annotation: Hornbostel-Sachs: 321.322
name: chanzy

description: The ranat kaeo is a Thai instrument similar to a xylophone consisting of glass bars of varying lengths.
name: ranat kaeo

description: The hotchiku is a Japanese end-blown bamboo flute.
name: hotchiku

description: The violino piccolo is a stringed instrument of the baroque period. Most examples are similar to a child's size violin in size and are tuned a third or a fourth higher.
name: violino piccolo

description: Also know and "flat-top", it is a hollow-body acoustic guitar strung with steel strings.
name: steel-string acoustic guitar

description: The tenor trombone is a trombone pitched in B♭.
name: tenor trombone

description: Popular late 16th to early 17th, it is the bass member of the lira family with between 9 and 16 strings and a fretted neck.
name: lirone

description: An archtop guitar is a steel-stringed acoustic or semi-acoustic guitar with a distinctive arched top, which is particularly popular with jazz players.
name: archtop guitar

description:
Also known as ektara, it has a body of wood or coconut with a membrane at the bottom. Attached to the sides is a handle-like neck of split bamboo from which a single string is suspended and attached to the membrane.
For the one string lute also called "ektar" see tumbi.
name: gopichant

description: Without strings or membranes, sound is created by the whole instrument vibrating.
annotation: Hornbostel-Sachs: 1
name: idiophone

description: The guan is a Chinese double reed wind instrument made from hardwood or bamboo.
name: guan

description: Family of quadruple reed oboes.
annotation: https://th.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E0%B9%81%E0%B8%A1%E0%B9%88%E0%B9%81%E0%B8%9A%E0%B8%9A:%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%84%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B7%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%87%E0%B8%94%E0%B8%99%E0%B8%95%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B5%E0%B9%84%E0%B8%97%E0%B8%A24. เครื่องเป่า1. มีลิ้น	ปี่นอก ปี่กลาง ปี่ใน ปี่ชวา ปี่มอญ ปี่ไฉน ปี่กาหลอ แคน ปี่จุม ปี่อ้อ ปี่แน ปี่ภูไท
name: pi

description: The tamborim is a small frame drum from Brazil.
name: tamborim

description: Used in various performances (capoeira angola, caboclo, etc) and samba music, it is usually made of metal and filled with grains, pebbles or the like.
name: ganzá

description: Klong that are large barrel drums from Thailand. They are played in a pair using wooden sticks and are used in the piphat ensemble.
name: klong that

description: Almost completely disappeared by the 20th century, modern revivals based on museum examples are now used by Swedish folk musicians.
name: säckpipa

description: A gong bass drum is a large single drumhead which resembles a gong.
name: gong bass drum

description: The zhaleika is a single reed hornpipe from Russia.
annotation: Hornbostel-Sachs: 422.211.2
name: zhaleika

description: The tinya is a small drum used in the traditional music of the Andes.
name: tinya

description: The nabal is a long, straight brass horn used in Korean traditional music.
name: nabal

description: Made of dried gourd. Struck with hands or objects.
name: calabash

description: The minipiano is a type of piano in which the sound producing mechanism is positioned below the keyboard, allowing an economical use of space.
name: minipiano

description: A guitar synthesizer is any one of a number of systems that allow a guitar player to play synthesizer sound.
name: guitar synthesizer

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro two harmonic flute
description: A longer version of the kōauau, it is from 30-40 cm up towards 60 cm in length and often made of bone and hardwoods such as porokaiwhiria, mataī and tutu.
name: pōrutu

description: Three-parts drumset (baandu, funde and kete) commonly used in Burru and Nyabinghi musics.
name: akete

description: Ancient Central Asian/Persian string instrument, ancestor of the Iranian oud. it was an important instrument in pre-Islamic Iran and Persia. The current “Persian barbat” is more similar to the oud.
name: barbat

description: Traditionally consisting of two long wooden planks with corn-husks attached for vibration and hit with long, thick sticks called Makilak, today the planks are shorter and can be made of many other materials like stone, wood or metal and are hit with shorter, lighter sticks.
name: txalaparta

description: Electromechanical piano (not to be confused with electronic piano) designed and produced by Hohner in the 1960 and 70s.
name: Pianet

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro small cross-blown flute
description: Cross-blown flute made of stone, bone or wood. It is 10 to 39 cm long, with usually 3 holes, but everything from none to 5 is known.
name: kōauau

description: Traditional musical instruments of the Māori people of New Zealand. Consists of gourds (hue), shell flutes (pu), wooden flutes (koauau), wind roarers and other natural materials.
name: taonga pūoro

description: Bass member of the garifuna drum group.
name: segunda

description: Electromechanical piano with stainless steel reeds and an amplified pick-up. Not to be confused with "cembalo" which is another name for Harpsichord.
name: Cembalet

description: Large wide tube with a very strongly flaring bell, the telescoping creates only subtle fluctuating overtones. It inspired the name of the anti-tank weapon.
name: bazooka

description: As long as a trumpet, it shares the piston valve design of both instruments with a mellow sound between the two.
name: flumpet

description: Usually accompanying sitar on ragas, the fretless instrument comes in different sizes: largest; male-voice, smaller; female-voice and smallest; the instrument-accompanying "tanpuri".
name: tanpura

description: The bolon is a traditional harp-lute played in several African countries.
name: bolon

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro long one-holed flute
description: Long wooden flute with a notched open top and a single finger hole near the end.
name: pūmotomoto

description: Used in folk medicine and shamanistic rituals.
name: temür khuur

description: Electronic bass organ, proto-keytar.
name: tubon

description: Similar to the north Indian shahnai, it has a 95 cm long hardwood body with 7 finger holes and 5 wax-fillable tuning holes and a wide flaring wooden bell; shorter variants have a metal bell.
name: nadaswaram

description: Made of an equine jawbone, it is used in traditional Latin American music as a rattle.
name: quijada

description: a Spanish plucked cittern, it is also played in the Spanish diaspora.
name: laúd

description: A cross between a saxophone and a duduk invented and played by Alexander Berne.
name: saduk

description: Tenor member of the garifuna drum group.
name: primero

description: Six-stringed lute-harp from Wassoulou, West Africa. Traditionally played by hunters, its resonator box is made of calabash covered by animal skin.
name: donso ngɔni

description:
For the instrument known as "chinese musette", see suona.
For the oboe also known as musette, see piccolo oboe.
Also known as baroque musette, it was a small bagpipe used predominantly by French court and nobility in the 1600-1700's.
name: musette de cour

disambiguation: prim, small Serbo-Croatian plucked string instrument
description: Smallest member of the Serbo-Croatian tamburica orchestra, it is usually the lead or "prim" instrument. It can either have one double string and three single strings (prim/bisernica) or two double strings and two single strings (bisernica).
annotation: Note that wikipedia is incorrect about an alternate name being "samica" that is a related but different instrument, a predecessor not used in the tamburtiza orchestra, but rather as a standalone folk instrument.
name: bisernica

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro wooden dual-voiced flute
description: Made of wood and shaped after the casemoth cocoon, it can be played as both a flute (female voice) and a trumpet (male voice).
name: pūtōrino

disambiguation: bass viol with guitar frets and tuning
description: Invented in 1823, it had a body like a medieval fiddle, but had frets and tuning like the guitar.
name: arpeggione
