description: Sopilka (generally) refers to a type of fife used in Ukrainian traditional music.
name: sopilka

description: The tololoche is a traditional musical instrument from northern Mexico, similar but smaller than the European double bass.
name: tololoche

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro gong made of jade and bone
description: Gong made of pounamu; greenstone and pilot-whale bone with a striker made of akeake, a hardwood.
name: pahū pounamu

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro wooden announcement trumpet
description: Up to 2,5 meters long, this wooden trumpet was used for a variety of announcements like war, welcoming people and kumara planting.
name: pūkaea

description: The bajo sexto is a Mexican string instrument with 12 strings in 6 double courses.
name: bajo sexto

description: Important to the Garifuna culture, it consists of two drums, the tenor, primero and the bass, segunda, each is made of hollowed out wood with membranes of pig, sheep or deer.
name: garifuna drum

description: Mongolian mouth harp. There are two types: temür/tömör khuur (steel) and khulsan khuur (bamboo).
name: aman khuur

description: Harmonica/accordion hybrid where the bellows for the accordion bit with buttons/keys receive air though the user blowing into the instrument like an harmonica.
name: accordina

disambiguation: uses analogue circuits to produce sound
description: Using analogue circuits and techniques to produce sound electronically, the first types where created in the 1920's with thermionic valves and other electromechanical machineries.
name: analog synthesizer

description: The luthéal is a kind of hybrid piano which extends the register possibilities of a standard piano, created by Georges Cloetens.
name: luthéal

disambiguation: early analogue synth with various sounds and "vibrato" keyboard
description: One of the first analogue synths, it had a filter bank with 15 sliders for different sounds, and a “vibrato” inducing keyboard based on the ondes Martenot’s.
name: ondioline

description: Chiefly Scandinavian, these bronze age natural brass horns were ritualistically buried in pairs.
name: bronze lur

disambiguation: extralong spinet with deep bass register
description: Exceptionally long spinet, with multiple strings choirs, its bass-tones were produced by longer, not thicker strings.
name: spinettone

description: The rototom is a drum which has no shell and is tuned by rotating.
name: rototom

description: The bass oboe is a double reed woodwind instrument which is about twice the size of a regular oboe.
name: bass oboe

description:
Not to be confused by the European renaissance bassoon dulcian.
Not to be confused with several Spanish bagpipes also called "gaita".
Widely used in Spanish communities it has many different names and a conical shape.
name: dulzaina

description: A mandolute is a North African fretted string instrument which combines a traditional oud string format with five pairs of metal strings.
name: mandolute

description: Originating in Central Asia, it gained symbolic value to the Turks who used it in Ottoman marching-bands. It is 2-2,5 m long, has a bronze crescent shape with bells and jangles attached.
name: çevgen

disambiguation: free reed aerophone with pitching pipes
description: Free reed melodica-like instrument that is worn like an accordion, with differing length pipes which control the pitch.
name: claviola

disambiguation: čelović or csello, counter Serbo-Croatian plucked string instrument
description: Counterpoint member of the Serbo-Coatian tamburica orchestra, it is guitar like like the bugarija. It can have two double strings and two single strings (čelović) but now four single strings are more common (čelo/čelović). The čelović is a different pitch than the čelo.
name: čelo

disambiguation: electronic keyboard, forerunner to analogue synthesizers
description: An early analogue synthesizer, it had a vacuum tube oscillator and high/low pass filtering to produce vibrato.
name: clavioline

description: Small piano with drop action stickers manufactured from around 1930 to the early 1990s.
name: piano spinet

description: Played in folk music of Hungary and Transylvanian regions, its 3-4 strings are plucked or struck with a stick, and its soundbox is made of thick maple, poplar or willow wood.
name: ütőgardon

description: An effects device to be clamped on the bridge, it produces “synthesizer-like” sounds.
name: gizmo

description: A dolceola is a musical instrument resembling a miniature piano, but which is in fact a zither with a keyboard.
name: dolceola

disambiguation: oboe-like double reed from South America
description: A relative of the shawm, it was introduced to central and south-america by the Spanish in the sixteenth and seventeenth century.
name: chirimía

disambiguation: pair of double-reed and drum. from South America.
description: Much like the pipe and tabor, the chirimía and drum is a South American cousin.
name: chirimía and drum

description: A lute from West Africa, made of wood or gourd.
name: ngɔni

disambiguation: Modern ngoni made of calabash with more strings
description: Modern derivative of the donso ngɔni, it comes with more strings and is made of calabash. It became an important instrument in the rise of the Wassoulou music in the 80's and 90's.
name: kamale ngɔni

description: The sarrusophone is a family of transposing musical instruments, intended to serve as a replacement in wind bands for the oboe and bassoon.
name: sarrusophone

description: The krar is a five or six-stringed bowl-shaped lyre from Eritrea and Ethiopia.
name: krar

description: Second smallest member of the Serbo-Croatian tamburica orchestra, there are often two, first and second bass. It can either have three double strings or two double strings and three single strings.
name: brač

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro conch shell trumpet
description: Trumpet made of conch shell, it has a beautifully carved wooden mouthpiece. It was for signalling, but also ceremonial and ritual use.
name: pūtātara

disambiguation: guitar/Viola caipira like plucked string instrument
description: Distinctly asymmetric in contrast to typical guitar, its timbre is a combination of the harpsichord (pt:cravo) and the Viola caipira. It can have six or twelve nylon or steel strings and are produced solely by company Giannini.
annotation: An instrument designed by brazilian composer Paulinho Nogueira, it is distinctly asymmetric in contrast to typical guitar.The timbre is like a combination of the harpsichord (pt:cravo) and the Viola caipira. Craviolas can be six-string or twelve-string (either nylon or steel) and are produced solely by company Giannini.
name: craviola

description: The piccolo oboe is the smallest and highest pitched member of the oboe family.
name: piccolo oboe

description: Electric instrument from the 1930's with a resistor wire and moving metal plate.
name: trautonium

description: conical goatskin frame-drum originating with the Yoruba people of West Africa, it is also found in Afro-Caribbean and Afro-Latin American cultures.
name: ashiko

description: Used for folk songs, particularly by young girls.
name: khulsan khuur

description: Small Polish traditional fiddle.
name: oktawka

description:
Not to be confused with the tambourine.
For the Brazilian frame-drum hit with a whisk see tamborim.
Side drum, often with one or more snares, worn by one person and beaten by one hand, it is often combined with tabor pipes.
name: tabor

description: Made of wood like mataī or tutu, this long flute has a transverse blowing hole with a fipple like European flutes but finger holes in the style of the traditional pōrutu.
name: rehu

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro swung whistling gourd
description: A hollowed out gourd (hue) with one to three holes, swung around creating a whistling, chattering sound that resembled birds.
name: poi āwhiowhio

description: Made of wood, bone or stone, it has a long string attached. When spun around it produces a deep, loud whizzing sound that can be heard from far away.
name: pūrerehua

description: A Turkish drum used in the traditional Ottoman military bands.
annotation: http://maviboncuk.blogspot.com/2012/10/ottoman-kettle-drums-kos-timpani.html
name: kös

description: European mediaeval struck string instrument, similar to the psaltery and a possible ancestor of the piano. Basically it is a dulcimer with keys.
name: dulce melos

disambiguation: Large South Indian fretless Carnatic slide lute
description: 13th century or earlier South Indian fretless slide lute used in Carnatic music. Hollow body made of jack-fruit with a secondary resonator of hollowed out gourd, it has 6 main, 3 drone and 11-12 sympathetic strings with a sliding block of hardwood to vary pitch. Much like the North Indian vichitra veena is to the rudra veena, chitra veena is to the Saraswati veena.
name: chitra veena

description: MIDI controller with a marimba-layout inspired control deck.
name: marimba lumina

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro small vessel flute
description: Small vessel flute made of wood, clay, bone or soft stone like soapstone, it has 4 holes and is played with the nose or mouth.
name: nguru

description: Bell as found on bicycles, sound is made by internal spring loaded hammer, not unlike alarm-clock.
name: bicycle bell

description: Made portable with a shoulder-strap like a guitar, this electric keyboard has sound controls on the neck.
name: keytar

description: Chord rhythm member of the Serbo-Croatian tamburica orchestra, it is guitar like. It has one double string D and three single strings.
name: bugarija

description: Ancient bowed fiddle, once popular in Western India and Sri Lanka.
name: ravanahatha

disambiguation: begeš, large bass Serbo-Croatian plucked string instrument
description: Bass member of the Serbo-Croatian tamburica orchestra, it is contrabass like. It has four thick metal strings.
name: berda

disambiguation: A smaller harpsichord, strings at an angle
description: A smaller harpsichord, often with the strings at 30 degrees from the keyboard.
name: spinet

description: The buisine was a type of straight medieval trumpet usually made of metal.
name: buisine

description: The citole is an archaic musical instrument, similar to and a distant ancestor of the modern guitar.
name: citole

description: Ancient pipe originating in Europe, with analogies all over the world, it is often combined with tabor drums.
name: three-hole pipe

description:
Improved further by Jaffar Khan, it had a wooden soundboard, the fingerboard covered with iron and all strings are steel or bronze.
Less common today, it was used for Dhrupad style music.
name: sursingar

description: Known from the Viking age, this natural brass trumpet/horn was made of wood or birch bark.
name: birch lur

description: Known in Persia as far back as the 14th century, it consists of glass containers, tuned by either being filled with water or later being of different sizes. Played by rubbing dampened fingers on the rims.
name: glass harp

description: Round-backed lute ancestral to the guitar.
name: gittern

description: The suka is a once-extinct fiddle from Poland.
name: suka

disambiguation: pair of flute and drum, each played by one hand
description: Originally an early European combination of a drum (tambourine) and pipe (fipple flute) were pipe was played by one hand and drum beaten by the other. It was chiefly used for dancing music. It has analogies all over the world.
name: pipe and tabor

description: Small white electric thumb piano with metal tines and an electromagnetic pickup.
name: Guitaret

description: Six holed fipple flute used traditionally in pastoral settings like its cousin the spilåpipa.
name: härjedalspipa

description: Whirring, spinning disks of many shapes, sizes and materials. When blown on, they also create a well of different humming sounds.
name: porotiti

description: Sound chip from various video game consoles, computers and similar, used for music, chiefly in bitunes and chiptunes.
name: game console sound chip

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro long necked conch trumpet
description: A pūtātara with a long wooden mouth piece, it has a deeper timbre than the pūtātara.
name: pūpakapaka

description: Based on the polyrhythm of the Afrikan kora, kalimba and Japanese koto, it is electro-acoustic with a stainless steel frame with 24 nylon strings and an integral piezoelectric sensor.
name: Gravikord

description: Improved by Johann Christoph Denner sometime around 1730, its "coiled snake" bore now is conical, in addition it is played through a removable metal curled mouth piece.
name: baroque rackett

description: Four-stringed banjo-like lute from West Africa, traditionally played by griots. Made of hollowed out wood with an animal hide as membrane.
name: jeli ngɔni

disambiguation: Bass member of the viol family
description: Most common viol member today, it was the bass-range viol in the original consort.
name: bass viol

description: While today it is obscure, it was developed and improved for 400 years. The French flageolet has four holes in the front and two thumb holes in the back.
name: flageolet

description: Pipes of bamboo with goat or calfskin membranes, the pitches depend largely on tube-lenght, it is the ancestor to the octoban. Modern variants are usually made of wood, plastic or metal with plastic membranes.
annotation: Hornbostel–Sachs classification 	211.211.1(Open ended cylindrical drum)
name: boobam

description:
Having 4 metal strings, it is carved from a single piece of wood into a particular shape similar to the Sarinda, it has 3 soundholes, two on each side of the short neck and one under the bridge which is membrane-covered.
Not to be confused with the Uyghur spike fiddle ghijak.
name: ghaychak

description: Two rods, one is held in the mouth, which works as a resonance chamber while chanting and singing, the other is used for tapping and scraping, creating rhythm.
name: pākuru

disambiguation: Ancient Afghan plucked lute member of the bowed rebab family
description: Related to bowed instrument rebab, it is played in many countries, from India to Afghanistan. It's made of wood and covered with a membrane and has 3 melody strings, 3 drone strings and 11/12 resonance strings.
name: rubab

description: Popular in the renaissance, it was small and portable with two bellows and brass reeds.
name: regal

description: Originating from Henan province, this fretless huqin has the accustomary two strings, but is made of wood.
name: zhuihu

description: Sacred cylindrical goat or cattle rawhide drum, traditionally it was held with straps or placed on a stand and played horizontally while walking to battle, on special state occasions and religious ceremonies.
name: junjung

disambiguation: Historical hybrid between English and German style concertinas
description: Bisonoric and button layout like the German, reeds and hexagonal ends like the english, this concertina was created to rival the popular German variant imported into England.
name: Anglo concertina

disambiguation: wooden tiger scraped with bamboo whisk
description: From atleast 600 BC, it is made of wood to resemble a tiger with its spine made into notches. Notches are scraped to produce sound, it was used in ensemble with zhu.
annotation: Hornbostel-Sachs 112.211
name: yu

description: Invented (or at least made popular) by Blue Man Group, it is made of alternating length PVC pipes and hit with sticks or flaps. It is popular with street musicians.
name: tubulum

description: Meant as an improvement on the flageolet design, the English flageolet had six finger holes in the front and one thumb hole in the back.
name: English flageolet

description: Invented by European luthiers in the first half of the 18th century, it had 6 to 7 single or double courses of gut strings and a long neck with either sharp or shallow angled pegbox.
name: mandora / gallichon

description: Also known as dangubica or kuterevka, it is similar to the bisernica and the ancestor of the entire tamburica ensemble. This plucked long-necked lute has two double strings and is played solo.
name: samica

description: Used in traditional kabuki and bunraku theatre, it consists of two hardwood pieces tied together with ornamental cord.
name: hyoshigi

description: Made of palmyra leaves that act as a resonator and a bamboo-tube stuck with wooden pegs where the plucked strings are attached, this traditional Indonesian instrument has an important place in folk history. It is still being used and modernised.
name: sasando

description: Castanets of wood, bone, bivalve shells or even flax leaf.
name: tōkere

description: Its origins can be sourced almost 5000 years ago, this Iraqi string instrument is the forefather of several instruments around the world. Its name means coconut or acorn, while originally made of walnut, it is today of coconut and fish-skin or heart-membrane.
name: djoza

disambiguation: ensemble of 1st violin, 2nd violin, viola and cello
description: Chamber ensemble of four players (two violins, one viola, one cello).
name: string quartet

description: Originating 1590 or earlier and made of wood or ivory, it had nine parallel cylindrical bores joined up at the top and bottom creating a continuous bore like a curled up snake. Its reed is attached to a center pirouette.
name: renaissance rackett

description: Small bass viol, specialised for intricate polyphonics, it had a flatter bridge than the other bass viols.
name: lyra viol

description: Medieval or possibly older, it was historically made of goat-horns or, less commonly, clay. With only a few holes and a single octave range it was used pastorally. Modern revival variants are more complicated and are usually made of cattle-horn.
name: gemshorn

description: Predecessor of the modern classical guitar, it had gut strings and even gut frets. First described in 1555, it surpassed the Renaissance lute's popularity.
name: baroque guitar

description: Larger bass drum also known as thunder or pope smasher, it has a double goat skin membrane and is hit with a padded mallet. Important in the Jamaican Burru music and Rastafari movement, it is part of the Nyabinghi/Akete drums.
name: baandu

disambiguation: New modern streamlined family of violins
description: New Violin Family of eight proportionally-sized violins developed mainly by Carleen Hutchins, each based directly on the standard violin and its acoustic properties, thus their sound is at a more homogeneous pitch "near the two middle open strings."
annotation: [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/837c7244-ece8-47ff-b215-78f4aa4f227d|Treble violin][https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/ba6af31f-8b2f-4c5e-903e-882f88f6d3a6|Soprano violin]Mezzo violin[https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/837c7244-ece8-47ff-b215-78f4aa4f227d|Alto violin][https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/c7a69b51-7105-4d4c-ab4a-ec118e24d1f0|Tenor violin][https://tickets.metabrainz.org/browse/INST-248|Baritone violin]Small bass violinContrabass violin
name: violin octet

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro flax leaf balls used in dancing
description: Flax leaf balls filled with seeds, swung around to create rhythmic and visual patterns. An important element in the dance also known as poi.
name: poi

description: Wood accordina with piano keys invented in Italy.
name: vibrandoneon

disambiguation: ancient predecessor of the Morin khuur
description: Counter-trapezoid shaped Mongolian fiddle, it is the ancestor of the Morin khuur.
name: chuurqin

description: Popular in the fifteenth century, it was a combination of a pipe organ and harpsichord, often with two keyboards, one for the strings and one for the pipes mounted underneath.
name: claviorganum

description: Traditional Catalan double reed of medieval origin. Used for cobla music in the 19th century, it mostly disappeared: current tarotas are a modern re-invention.
name: tarota

disambiguation: ensemble of violin, cello and piano
description: Chamber ensemble of three players (one piano, one violin, one cello).
name: piano trio

disambiguation: ensemble of violin, viola and cello
description: Chamber ensemble of three players (one violin, one viola, one cello).
name: string trio

description: Used in folk music and educationally in Korean schools, it is a notched, vertically end-blown bamboo flute which, like its bigger cousin the Tungso, was derived from the Chinese xiao in the 19th century.
name: danso

description: Thin quiet mouth harp like instrument made of wood or bone.
name: rōria

disambiguation: Treble/soprano member of the viol family
description: The treble, descant or soprano member of the viol family.
name: treble viol

disambiguation: Tenor member of the viol family
description: Tenor member of the viol family.
name: tenor viol

description: More accurately a virginals, its strings were arranged in a pattern creating an oval shape, allowing for a stronger, more compact configuration. 2 examples survive today.
name: oval spinet

description: Guitar-bouzouki hybrid with guitar body and 4 pairs of strings like the bouzouki, developed separately several different luthiers, among them Stefan Sobell (bouzar) and Davy Stuart (gouzouki).
name: bouzar / gouzouki

description: Made of tubing with holes that may have everything from none to two reeds, water instead of air comes out of the holes. Sound is produced by covering the holes with fingers, altering the flow of water through the holes.
name: hydraulophone

description: Used in gagaku, this traditional bamboo flute has six holes.
name: kagurabue

description: Inspired by the violin in 1920, Hellenic luthiers combined parts of the old Cretan lyra with the violin.
name: viololyra

description: Plucked idiophones have spikes, nails or flexible tongues ("lamellae") that are plucked in various ways to produce sound.
name: plucked idiophone

description: Wooden flute of the simple-system type, popular in Irish folk music.
name: Irish flute

disambiguation: Family of the brass instrument trumpet
description: Family of the brass instrument trumpet.
name: trumpet family

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro tiny gourd nose flute
description: Nose flute made of gourd with two holes. While it is tiny, it has a huge sound.
name: kōauau ponga ihu

description: In the form of a piano accordion, the keys control the output, pitch and sound, bellows control only volume. Sold by Hohner since 1952, it has gone through many modernisations through the years.
name: elektronium

description: Shaped like an eighth-note with a cute face, it is played with one hand fingering the neck and the other squeezing the head to create wavering sound.
name: Otamatone

disambiguation: Brass valveless ancestor of the modern trumpet
description: Ancestor of the modern trumpet, it is valveless with a mouthpiece and at-least one coil, it has an origin in military use.
name: natural trumpet

description: Hunting horn carved out of ivory, it was widely used in Medieval wars to alarm or increase soldiers' morale.
name: olifant

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro single string bow
description: also just "kū", a mouthbow with a single string, struck with a light implement of bone or wood.
name: te kū

description: introduced in 1938, it was a popular American educational instrument.
name: Tonette

description: Used to teach children how to play, it is a simplified zither shaped like a trapezoid.
name: lap harp

description: Played using circular breathing, it is made of twin bamboo reeds with five to six holes. From the middle-east, it is used in traditional music and as a accompaniment to belly dancing and dabke.
name: mijwiz

description: Invented in 1966 by vox, and in 1969 by Bob Murrell, it is an electric guitar with electronic organ wiring and knobs added.
name: guitorgan

description: Sixteenth century predecessor of the violoncello, it was fretless with f-holes and had at first three, then later four, strings tuned in fifths.
name: bass violin

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro large bass gourd
description: Large gourd (hue) with no finger-holes, it is blown like a jug and has a booming bass sound.
name: hue puruhau

disambiguation: Alto member of the viol family
description: Alt, alto or contralto member of the viol family. Not to be confused with the Viola of the violin family, known as "Alto" in French.
name: alto viol

description: Reinvented several times in different lands, it combines banjo body and neck of mandolin, it is tuned like it and the violin.
name: banjolin

description: Please use Viola da Gamba with credit "viol" for generic / unspecified viol credits, and not this one. Developed in the 15th century from vihuelists starting to play with bows, viols have frets, flat backs, sloped shoulders, c-holes and are tuned in fourths.
annotation: Developed in the 15th century from Vihuelists starting to play with bows, viols have frets, flat backs, sloped shoulders, c-holes and are tuned in fourths.There are two distinct groupings of viols, one were the members are:* [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/47ce1322-27d4-42ad-a020-f3dccfab9431|Pardessus viol]* [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/85d0d4b3-2bf0-4925-a3ad-3ebb49d04728|Treble/Diskant or Dessus viol]* [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/4d62efe7-5a87-458c-8476-049c86ed2412|Alto viol]* [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/47005798-5f13-4768-b16b-6e88350358e3|Tenor viol]* [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/7cbd040f-6217-48d0-ac43-3e8ecb4b4b0b|Bass viol] (This is the most common and sometimes known as "Consort Bass", unspecified "Viol" credits are most likely this.)* [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/cb2793f8-cbab-4eec-b54c-b5ee77956caf|Great Bass Viol or Violone in G]* [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/cb2793f8-cbab-4eec-b54c-b5ee77956caf|Contra Bass Viol or Violone in D]and one were the members are:* [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/85d0d4b3-2bf0-4925-a3ad-3ebb49d04728|Soprano viol] (treble)* [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/4d62efe7-5a87-458c-8476-049c86ed2412|Alto viol]* [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/47005798-5f13-4768-b16b-6e88350358e3|Tenor viol]* [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/cb2793f8-cbab-4eec-b54c-b5ee77956caf|Bass Viol] (violone called bass viol)
name: viol family

description: Small fretted hybrid instrument with a banjo body and a ukulele neck, popular in the 1920-30.
name: banjo-ukulele

disambiguation: Smallest member of the viol family
description: Pardessus or sopranino member of the viol family.
name: pardessus de viole

description: Unisonoric concertina with hexagonal sides and concertina reeds.
name: English concertina

description: Instruments used in the traditional music of the Basque people.
name: traditional basque ensemble

disambiguation: Catalonian double reed descendant of shawm
description: Derived from the tenor shawm, it was independently developed in Catalonia by oboe player Andreu Turon in the 19th century. Made of ginjoler wood with a metal cone, it is used in the traditional cobla and sardana music.
name: tenora

description: Effectively a small electric guitar-piano hybrid, it is played by tapping the multiple isometric arranged strings that are stretched over a long flat board.
name: harpejji

description: Like a piano, but here keyed hammers hit tuning forks.
name: dulcitone

disambiguation: late 18th century portable piano with shoulder strap
description: Portable piano with shoulder strap invented in 1795, it is a descendant of the Baroque Bauchladenspinett and a sort of early precursor of the keytar.
name: orphica

description: Also known as kette or keteh, it is the smallest size/pitch drum. It has a tight goat skin membrane and it is struck with the fingertips. Important in the Jamaican Burru music and Rastafari movement, it is part of the Nyabinghi/Akete drums.
name: repeater

description: Middle size/pitch drum, it has a slack goat skin membrane and it is hit with the palms. Important in the Jamaican Burru music and Rastafari movement, it is part of the Nyabinghi/Akete drums.
name: fundeh

description: Gourd (hue) shakers with seeds intact
name: hue puruwai

description: National symbol of Estonia, related to Finnish kantele. While traditionally a small instrument with 5 to 7 strings, some newer versions are much bigger, with up to 50 strings.
name: kannel

description: Originating from 13th century Latvia, it is made of wood and have today nine to eleven, up to thirty-three strings tuned diatonically. Played horizontally on lap or table by plucking while muting chosen strings. Became in the 70's and 80's an important part of the folklore movement.
annotation: Hornbostel-Sachs classification of 314.122
name: kokle

disambiguation: Catalan valved shawm used in cobla
description: Catalan double-reed, created in the 19th Century by adding valves to the tarota. Used principally for cobla music.
name: tible

description: Its name variously used to describe the serpentone, the ophicleide and the bombardon, the modern cimbasso was developed by instrument making firm Pelitti under instruction guidance by Verdi; it had a forward facing bell and 3 to 6 valves. The modern instrument has a characteristic bend.
name: cimbasso

description: Diatonic button accordion used in traditional Basque ensemble.
name: trikiti

description: Made of wood, bone or metal, this ancient instrument is the forerunner to many other struck idiophones.
name: clapper

description: Very long metal bar fitted with strings and electric pickups, it makes a deep ominous booming sound and is often used in score.
annotation: translated from [https://ru.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blaster_Beam|russian wikipedia] (most comprehensive article):Бластер-бим (English: Blaster Beam) or simply бим (English: The Beam) - an electronic stringed musical instrument invented in the 1970s and best known for its use in the soundtrack of science fiction films Blaster Beam is a straight and flat metal beam several meters long, on the upper side of which stretched strings and pickups, like electric guitars. They play on it, striking the strings with their hands or with various objects, for example, metal tubes.Blaster-beam was invented in the early 1970's John Lazell and first used in his works by the composer Francisco Lupic, who produced several instruments of cast iron. Later another American composer Craig Huxley made his version of Beam from aluminium, 12 feet long. He played the blaster-beam using a shell from an artillery shell, striking the strings or traversing them, pressing to the body (like a pedal-style, a kind of slide guitar).Composer Jerry Goldsmith met Huxley while writing music for the film "Star Trek" in 1979 and used the sound of a blaster beam for a musical theme related to "V-ger".A grim, frightening sound transmitted the threat emanating from this mysterious object. Huxley himself in his youth played two episodic roles in the series "Star Trek".)The instrument was used to create sound design in a number of other fantastic films, as well as in experimental and popular music. Craig Huxley was familiar with Michael Jackson, and the sound of the blaster-beam was used in a number of songs by the latter, including Billie Jean and Beat It. Michael Stearns made his version of an aluminium blaster-beam for recording music for the film "Chronos". Composer Ber McCreery used a blaster beam to create the soundtrack for the movie "Cloverfield, 10"; On the instrument, Huxley himself played in his studio.
name: Blaster Beam

description: Made of clay with two layers of goat skin, it is used as a rhythmic accompaniment to shehnai players and is one of the instruments of the Baul community.
name: duggi

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro ancient struck idiophone
description: Made of resonating stone, wood or bone with a striker of stone, bone or hardwood, this ancient instrument was used for rhythm during chanting.
name: tumutumu

description: Made of thick aged bamboo, this notched end-blown flute may have had a buzzing membrane.
name: tungso

description: Traditionally used in samba and maracatu, it originates from the European military battalion. It is made of a 30-35 cm diameter metal barrel strung with a synthetic material, upon which a steel wire or guitar string is strung across.
annotation: Variants are as follows: * The deeper big box Caixas de guerra (or "war box"), its strap across waist or shoulder* The small thinner Tarol, its strap across the chest or shoulder, it is held "upwards"
name: caixa

description: Plastic horn often used at football matches in South Africa.
name: vuvuzela

disambiguation: Māori taonga pūoro large signalling drum
description: Logs or thick planks up to 9 meters long used as signalling drums, as gongs for both war and peace. Even living hollowed trees have been used as pahū.
name: pahū

description: Originating in Mewati community of Rahajastan, India, it is traditionally made of gourd with top and bottom cut off, with a goat hide membrane nailed to one opening and a gut string which ends in a bamboo piece attached to the membrane. The instrument is held in the armpit and played by plucking the string while pulling it.
name: bhapang

description: Fipple flute that became a symbol for the Basque folk revival.
annotation: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xirula ?http://web.archive.org/web/20091220035327/http://txistuaz.iespana.es/whatis.htm
name: txistu

description: More usually square than hexagonal, with long plate reeds.
name: German concertina

description: Small but long tom-toms set in groups of four or eight, they are a common addition in drumsets. Originally made of fibreglass, today also acrylic, aluminium or wood is used, and homemade ones of f.ex PVC are not uncommon.
name: octoban

description:
Unison course tuned 12 stringed electric guitar body with mandolin neck, it is tuned an octave higher than a conventional guitar, thus having the tonal range of the mandolin.
Not to be confused with flat-backed mandolin which is also sold as "mando-guitar".
name: mandoguitar

description: Originally introduced to Mongolia from China, it has 13 double wire-strings and a black lacquered wooden soundboard. Traditionally it was only played by townspeople.
name: yoochin

description: Small Catalan flageolet used in the cobla ensemble, unlike other tabor-pipes it is also played with both hands.
name: flabiol

disambiguation: Medium pitched gong-chime set in Javanese gamelan
description: One to two octaves below panerus, it plays elaborate melodies and is one of the most important instruments in the ensemble.
name: bonang barung

disambiguation: Small boat shaped zither used in Sundanese gamelan
description: Known as rincik "child" it has 15 steel strings, it has individual bridges and a sound-hole in the bottom.
name: kacapi rincik

disambiguation: Ten key metallophone used in Bali wayang.
description: Special version of the gendèr used in Gamelan gendèr wayang performances. Tuned in Slendro, one to two pairs are played using the same hand to both play and dampen the keys.
name: gendèr wayang

description:
Used traditionally by the Minang people of West Sumatra for love songs, in shamanic rites and for capturing tigers, this open end-blown bamboo flute can be decorated to resemble tiger-stripes. Played with a circular breathing technique, it is 75 cm long with 3 to 6 holes depending on subtype.
  • saluang darek "inland" 4 holes
  • saluang pauh/padang 6 holes
  • saluang sungai pagu 3 holes
name: saluang

description: Used in Spanish classic and popular music during the late 19th and early 20th century, it together with bandurria and laúd carried the melody in rondas and rondallas. It had six pairs of strings, tuned a fourth lower than bandurria, It fell out of use when contralto bandurria became common.
name: octavilla

disambiguation: Second deepest pitch gangsa used in Balinese gamelan
description:
Second lowest pitched of the gangsa, it has 4 to 7 bronze keys suspended over long bamboo resonators.
For the Sundanese bamboo xylophone also used in gamelan, see calung.
name: jublag

disambiguation: Metal plate percussion used in Javanese gamelan
description: Used in wayang puppetry, it is made of 1 to 4 iron (sometimes bronze) plates hung by strings, The puppeteer uses a small mallet set in the foot to hit the plate(s).
name: kepyak

disambiguation: Very large suspended Javanese barrel drum
description: Extra large double-headed water buffalo hide barrel drum. It is suspended from a rack and beat with mallet, it is used in central Javanese gamelan and for religious signalling purposes in mosques.
name: bedug

disambiguation: King-Size truncated cone kendang used in Sundanese gamelan
description: Played in ensemble with kulanter, it is set at an angle and played with hands or sticks. It has the designation of "mother".
name: kendhang indung

disambiguation: ensemble flute, clarinet, violin, cello and piano
description: Chamber ensemble of five players (flute, clarinet, violin, cello and piano). Originally required for Schönberg's Pierrot Lunaire, it became a fairly common combination for 20th century classical groups.
name: Pierrot ensemble

description: Used in folk music, bamboo is split into a pair of 40 cm long sticks which are hit together.
name: krap khū

description: Located in the Luray Caverns of Virginia USA, it is made of an electric console wired to mallets striking thirty-seven stalactites producing tones. This is a singular specific instrument, not an instrument type.
name: The Great Stalacpipe Organ

description: Made of various materials, clappers are struck together to keep rhythm and time for use in ceremonies and rituals and to accompany dancing and singing.
name: krap

disambiguation: Family of two sided laced drums used in various gamelan
description:
Used in many Southeast Asian countries, the body is made of woods like jackfruit or coconut, the heads of buffalo- and goat-hide.
There are 2 main groups:
  • The Java/Sunda set of 3 to 4 curve sided drums with heads of different sizes.
  • The Bali set of two pairs of straight sided drums, both heads same size.
annotation: The 2 main groupings consist of: * The conical () Java/Sunda set of 3 to 4 curve sided drums with heads of different sizes. * The cylindrical || Bali set of two pairs of straight sided drums, both heads same size.Actually there are 3 sets of Indonesian gamelan kendang: (other countries also have some.) * The Java set of 4 double conical drums: ** bassdrum		Kendhang gendhing or Kendhang ageng ** tenordrum	Kendhang wayang ** altdrum		Kendhang batangan or Kendhang ciblon ** sopranodrum	Kendhang ketipung * The Sunda set of 3 truncated cone drums: ** bassdrum		Kendhang gede  ** altdrum		Kendhang ciblon ** sopranodrum	Kendhang ketipung * The Bali cylindrical (or slightly truncated cone) set of 2 pairs of drums: ** high pitched kendang lanang ** low pithed kendan wadon
name: kendang

disambiguation: Deepest pitch gangsa used in Balinese gamelan
description: Largest and lowest pitched of the gangsa, it has 5 to 7 large metal bars suspended over long bamboo resonators.
name: jegogan

description: Generally consists of one to very many plates, sticks, or other objects hit with (or against) various types of mallets.
name: percussion idiophone

disambiguation: Penultimate pitch saron-family member used in Sundanese gamelan.
description: Called simply "demung", it is the largest and deepest pitched of the regular saron.
name: saron demung

disambiguation: Highest pitch saron-family member used in Sundanese gamelan.
description: Called simply "panerus", it has seven bronze keys resting on a decorated rancak box. Keys are hit by tabuh mallet with head of buffalo horn.
name: saron panerus

disambiguation: Very small bellows operated pipe organ
description: Constructed in medieval Europe to be as portable as possible, small upright wooden frame with keyboard contains a row of flute-pipes fed air from hand operated bellows.
name: portative

description: Introduced to Indonesia in the 15th century, this variant of the spike-fiddle rebab has two bowed metal strings with characteristically long tuning pegs and is made of hide-covered wood or coconut shell. It is the melody leader in gamelan and is also used in healing rituals.
name: Indonesian rebab

description: Set of 6 to 10 smaller hanging pitched bronze gongs with a protruding centre knob struck with tabuh beaters. Higher pitched than the gong ageng, it is often hung together with it.
name: kempul

disambiguation: Middle conical kendang used in both Javanese/Sundanese gamelan
description:
Middle sized kendang, it is used in lively and complex rhythms.
In Sunda it is known as kendhang ciblon.
name: kendhang batangan

description: A zither with a hollow or vaulted body, it can have several resonators.
name: tube zither

description:
Stick zither from Rajasthan. It is made of wood with at least two large gourd resonators, the strings rest on very high frets.

Not to be confused with the 13th century tritantri-vina which evolved into the bin via a five-string stick-zither also known as "jantar".
name: jantar

description: Set of 4 to 12 small metal gongs suspended in a string carriage, played by two to four players.
name: reyong

description: Developed chiefly as a folk instrument for accompanying singing and dancing, its front has a intricately carved soundhole and slants towards the bottom where the 5 double (sometimes triple courses) of thin steel strings are fastened with pins. The back can be rounded or flat.
name: chitarra battente

disambiguation: Smallest conical kendang used in both Javanese/Sundanese gamelan
description:
Smallest of the kendang, it is has a special two-instrument use with the gendhing.
In Sunda it is known as kendhang katipung.
name: kendhang ketipung

description: Free reeds with bellows attached, often in a square shape, thence called squeezebox.
name: bellowed reed

disambiguation: Deep pitch gangsa used in Balinese gamelan
description: Even lower pitched than the pemade , it also has 10 bronze keys suspended over tuned bamboo resonators that the player hits with a small hammer, often in a theatrical manner. It is the leader of the pokok melody.
name: ugal

disambiguation: Family of ancient Indian lute-like chordophones
description:
One of the two subfamilies of Indian chordophones, the South Indian gourd lute used in classical Carnatic music has a single gourd music-box (sometimes a secondary small resonator gourd) with an often hollow neck.
Commonly called just "veena" or "vina", the representative is Saraswati veena, and credits to just "veena" are usually that.
name: veena

disambiguation: Bamboo xylophone used in Sundanese gamelan
description:
Made of multiple vertical hung bamboo tubes with segments cut out to create different pitch. They can be played either hanging suspended or on a bamboo frame like a xylophone.
For the Balinese metallophone sometimes known as chalung or calung, see jublag.
name: calung

description: Shaken idiophone or rattle. Sound is produced by holding or containing usually small concussing parts.
name: shaken idiophone

disambiguation: Paired truncated cone kendang used in Sundanese gamelan
description: Always used together with the indung, dual child drums are divided into the katipung ("besar" or larger) and the kutiplak ("kecil" or smaller).
name: kendhang kulanter

disambiguation: Deepest pitch single octave metallophone used in Javanese gamelan
description: Used in Javanese gamelan, the 6(slendro)-7(pelog) bronze keys beat by a disk mallet(tabuh) are suspended above individual tube metal/bamboo resonators set in a 75 cm long wooden frame.
name: slenthem

description: Uses in Javanese gamelan and Balinese wayang, these range from 12 to 14 tuned bronze keys, all suspended over metal or bamboo resonators.
name: gendèr

disambiguation: ensemble of piano, violin, viola and cello
name: piano quartet

disambiguation: Special saron used for Wayang puppetry
description: Used in the Javanese Wayang puppet theatre, it has nine large bronze keys set in a decorated frame.
name: saron wayang

description: Large square spring-containing bellows operated by the feet, it was used by accordion players as bass accompaniment in early 20th century Wallonia.
name: footbass

description: Ensemble of multiple instruments of the viol family, usually including at least treble, tenor and bass viols.
name: viol consort

disambiguation: Low pitched cylindrical kendang used in Bali gamelan.
description: The larger and deeper pitched of the Bali kendang, it is the leader "female" drum.
name: kendang wadon

disambiguation: Middle pitch metallophone used in Javanese gamelan
description: Used for elaborate and complex parts, it has thinner but wider metal bars suspended above resonator rods, it is the middle-pitched member of the gendèr family.
name: gendèr barung

description: Similar to the Japanese taishogoto, it has an elongated teardrop shaped wooden body with button accordion like keys which plays the melody and sets chords.
name: akkordolia

description: Particular type of fiddle, long neck, often few strings and usually with a rather small soundbox, it has a spike at the end.
name: spike-fiddle

disambiguation: Obsolete deepest saron-family member used in Sundanese gamelan.
description: Unlike the other saron, its six-seven keys are not smooth, but bevelled or bossed, like the gendèr and the slenthem, which has largely replaced it in the modernised gamelan.
name: slentho

description: Consists of up to 21 hardwood bars suspended by pins and rope over an oft ornate wooden trapeze shaped box, the two springy beaters are made of buffalo horn.
name: gambang

description: Used in the chant, sēphā, a pair of squared bevelled rosewood sticks around 21 cm long and 3-4 cm thick.
name: krap sēphā

disambiguation: Small boxed double gong-chime used in Javanese gamelan
description: Always used with ketuk, it consists of two bronze kettle-gongs, pitched a note apart. Ached top bossed gongs are sat in the highly decorated rancak frame, beaten with tabuh beaters by the same person.
annotation: [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/beb10494-f892-4865-b2aa-9f4c21824ee0|Ketuk] and kempyang are always used together, the kempyang is higher pitch than the ketuk, both are hit by tabuh beaters and frequently played by the same person. Sometimes only ketuk is used, but kempyang is never used without ketuk. Both have a raised central boss, however the top around the boss is flat (setren) in the ketuk and more arched (jaler) in the kempyang.--◠-- ⸝-◠-⸜
name: kempyang

disambiguation: Arrangement of struck tuned stone bars.
name: lithophone

description: Used in royal ceremonies, played by striking against the palm, it is made of several pieces of wood, ivory and sheets of brass between two larger pieces of wood tied together by a string at one end.
name: krap phuang

description:
Flat-cut gourd sitar with 16 frets, 2 steel & 3 brass strings. In the 1820s it was used by Ghulam Mohammed to develop the surbahar.

Mistakenly re-named "Kachapi vina" in the 19th century by Tagore, that instrument was actually an ancient unrelated short-necked pear-shaped lute.
name: kachva sitar

disambiguation: Higest pitch metallophone used in Javanese gamelan
description: Used for simple ornamentation, it has thick small metal bars suspended above resonator rods, it is the highest pitched member of the gendèr family.
name: gendèr panerus

disambiguation: Bellowed free reed in a lute-like casing
description:
Not to be confused with mellophone, a brass valved instrument.
Wooden body shaped like a lute, it has a bellow operated by a handle at the bottom and buttons operating the reeds in the “neck”.
name: melophone

disambiguation: Lowest pitched gong-chime set in Javanese gamelan
description: Chiefly used in Yogyvanese gamelan, the largest and deepest pitched member of the bonang family of gong-chimes.
name: bonang panembung

disambiguation: Family of ancient Indian stick zither chordophones
description:
One of the two subfamilies of Indian chordophones, the North Indian stick zither used in classical Hindustani music has two (or more) large gourd sound resonators and a stick or tube body.
Commonly called "bin", "been" or "bean", the representative is rudra veena, and credits to just "bin" are usually that.
name: bīn

disambiguation: Highest pitched gong-chime set in Javanese gamelan
description: Used to play fast melodies, it is the highest pitched member of the bonang family of gong-chimes.
name: bonang panerus

disambiguation: Middle conical kendang used in javanese gamelan
description: Middle sized kendang, it was traditionally used for the wayang dance.
name: kendhang wayangan

disambiguation: Singular metal timekeeping gong-chime used in Balinese gamelan
description: Singular bronze gong-chime kettle set on a decorated jackfruit-wood box stand. Used as time or tempo keeper, it is struck on the boss with panggul beater, which provides reference point in the pokok.
name: kempli

description: Made of sandalwood or bamboo, 2 blocks are tied together with a string, a third with a ribbon. Part of the drum and clapper ensemble guban, but confusingly, the clapper alone can also be called guban.
name: paiban

description: Chiefly used in Southeast Asian music, these consist of from only 1 to several dozens of metal (often bronze) "kettles", set in a wide variety of different supports and played with mallets.
name: gong-chime

description: Originating with the Spanish influence on Filipino culture, it has 14 strings and a short neck with 16 to 20 frets. It is played with its close relative, the laúd.
name: octavina

disambiguation: High pitched cylindrical kendang used in Bali gamelan.
description: The smaller and higher pitched of the Bali kendang, it is the follower "male" drum.
name: kendang lanang

disambiguation: ensemble of two pianists playing on one piano
description: Chamber ensemble where two pianists play on the same piano at the same time.
name: piano four hands

annotation: sub: * Long-necked lutes * Short-necked lutes * Bowed lutes ** bowl fiddles ** spike fiddles * Harp-Lutes
name: lute family

description: Ensemble of four saxophones, generally SATBar.
name: saxophone quartet

description: From West Africa, it has multiple curved necks each with one string, sometimes played a harp and sometimes with stops like a lute.
name: pluriarc

description:
For the wheel-bowed instrument also called "lira", see hurdy-gurdy.
For the harp-like instrument, see lyre.
For the bowed lute, see Cretan lyra.
name: lira da braccio

description:
Used in India during the medieval period, it had a stick-zither body with 3 strings.
For the the long necked lute called “tritantri veena” in the 19 century, see “sitar”.
name: tritantri veena

disambiguation: Large high-pitch gong-chime used in Indonesian Gamelan
description: Related to bonang, it consists of 3 decorated rancak frames that each hold 2 large arched (jaler) bronze gong-chimes hit by heavy tabuh beater(s).
name: kenong

disambiguation: High pitch gangsa used in Balinese gamelan
description: Highest pitched gangsa, it has 10 brass or bronze keys suspended over short resonating bamboo pipes set in an heavily ornate case.
name: kantilan

description: Made of goatskin covered dried gourd, it has a single gut string bowed with a horsehair bow.
name: njarka

disambiguation: Boat shaped zither used in Sundanese gamelan
description: Known as indung "mother" or parahu "boat", it has 18 brass strings each with its own pyramid shaped bridge. Shaped like a boat, its sound hole is at the bottom.
name: kacapi indung

description: Composite chordophone, box zither where some or all strings are operated by typewriter-keys or buttons (keyboard).
name: keyed box zither

description: Deriving from the classical guitar, it has many modifications and playing techniques to create a more percussive sound. Originally having wooden tuning pegs like lutes and violins, it has a thinner, lighter build with "golpeadores" or tapping-plates and less sustain than the classical guitar.
name: flamenco guitar

description: Whole or half-pear shaped wooden body, it is partly fretted and has two string-courses; melody and drone. The name comes from Germanic words meaning bumblebee or buzzing.
name: hummel

description: Used by Australian Aboriginals to maintain rhythm in chants and traditionally to accompany didgeridoo. There are also Boomerang clapsticks.
name: clapstick

description: Generally consists of two completely equal or somewhat unsymmetrical sticks, plates, shells or similar hit together.
name: concussion idiophone

disambiguation: Lower pitch gangsa used in Balinese gamelan
description: Second highest pitched gangsa, it is deeper than the kantil but also has 10 brass or bronze keys suspended over short resonating pipes set in an heavily ornate case.
name: pemade

description: Constructed as the uttermost largest member of the violin family, it is up towards 4 meters and has three strings operated by levers and pedals.
name: octobass

disambiguation: Small boxed gong-chime used in Javanese gamelan
description: Always used with kempyang, it consists of a single bronze kettle-gong, pitched deeper than kempyangs'. Flat top bossed gong is sat in a highly decorated rancak frame, beaten with tabuh beaters by the same person.
annotation: Ketuk and [https://beta.musicbrainz.org/instrument/e42151f8-efb2-41e1-9aad-fb8fa115c233|kempyang] are always used together, the kempyang is higher pitch than the ketuk, both are hit by tabuh beaters and frequently played by the same person. Sometimes only ketuk is used, but kempyang is never used without ketuk. Both have a raised central boss, however the top around the boss is flat (setren) in the ketuk and more arched (jaler) in the kempyang.--◠-- ⸝-◠-⸜
name: kethuk

description: Scraper made of bones tied together with rope scraped with a conch-shell, in Catalonia it's scraped with a castanet. Ginebra is a variant made of cane.
name: arrabel

description: Effectively a bass sitar, it has 4 main, 3-4 chikari(drone) and 10-11 resonance strings strung over a wide wooden neck. Made of flat-cut gourd with a possible secondary resonator (tumba) it was invented in 1825 by sitar-player Ghulam Mohammed who wanted a deeper sound.
name: surbahar

disambiguation: Largest conical kendang used in both Javanese/Sundanese gamelan
description:
Largest or "ageng" of the kendang, it is still smaller than the bedug.
In Sunda it is known as kendhang gedé.
name: kendhang gendhing

disambiguation: Banana shaped bronze slit-drum used in javanese gamelan
description: Bent into a ladle or banana like shape, it is a pair of bronze slit-drums hit with tabuh beaters.
name: kemanak

description: Often used in group musical education and by street musicians, it consists of individual colourful hollow plastic tubes of various widths that are struck on various surfaces to produce sound, tubes can also be arranged and hit by mallets.
name: boomwhacker

description: Important in Yue, Kunkqu and Peking opera, it consists of the drum bangu and the clapper paiban. Drum is played by one hand and clapper with the other.
name: guban

description: Used in both gamelan and Wayang puppet theatre, it consists of two small cymbals sets; the bottom pair affixed in a highly decorated rancak rack, their lose counterparts attached together by string.
name: kecer

disambiguation: Family of bronze gong-chime sets used in Javanese gamelan
description: Consisting of bossed bronze kettle-like gongs arranged in elaborately decorated wooden frames, these are hit with tabuh beaters.
name: bonang

description: Similar to panerus with which it has a different but overlapping range, it has 6 bronze keys tuned for the slendro key.
name: saron peking

description: Made of metal with many small notches scraped with a brush or hair pick, it is used in merengue típico.
name: güira

description: Class of instruments where the body is a simple stick with one to many strings attached, may also have up to several usually gourd or wood resonators.
name: stick zither

disambiguation: Medieval Indian evolution of the Afghan (kabuli) rabab
description: Larger, with a longer neck than the kabuli rabab, it has a hide covered soundbox and wooden fingerboard with mostly gut strings, it was developed during medieval times by Tansen, who improved it and gave it metal sympathetic strings.
name: seni rebab

disambiguation: ensemble of two pianists playing on separate pianos
description: Chamber ensemble where two pianists play on a different piano each.
name: piano duo

disambiguation: Box zither used in Sundanese gamelan
description: Inspired by western zithers, it has 20 strings and is flatter than the other kacapis.
name: kacapi siter

description: There are two kinds, boat shaped "mother" and "child" ones, originally made of a single piece of wood and descended from the kacapi pantun as used in epic story. And a flat box-zither made of wood used from the 1950's and in experimental music.
name: kacapi

disambiguation: Middle pitch saron-family member used in Sundanese gamelan.
description: Often called simply "saron", it plays the basic, balungan melody.
name: saron barung

description: Not to be confused with the Persian lute ghaychak.
name: ghijak

description: Developed from the 1960's and used mainly in the 70-80's, it was a cheaper and more portable simplification of the mellotron, emulating string ensembles. Its later hybrid development with the electronic organ created "polyphonic ensemble" synthesizers.
name: string synthesizer

description: Developed from the veuze and often accompanying the bombard, the small high-pitched, singular octave bagpipe is used in Breton folk dancing.
name: biniou

description: Smaller than the charango, it has 10 strings.
name: walaycho

description: Larger than the gallega, it has been in use since atleast the 13th century, traditionally with only one chanter and drone, it has very colourfully decorated fur.
name: gaita asturiana

description: Used in folklore music of Andes, it is a descendant of European bass drum. It has a shoulder strap and two soft headed mallets used to strike the goat or llama pelt membrane.
name: bombo legüero

description:
For the similarly named single-reed woodwind see chalumeau.
For the European instrument, see shawm.
Name derived from the Portuguese name of shawm, it was imported by Iberian traders. It is used in kabuki theatre and by ramen street vendors.
name: charumera

description: Known since 1400, traditionally in military context, today it is the most widespread and famous of bagpipes.
name: Great Highland bagpipe

disambiguation: Italian double reed with conical bore
description:
For the small flute used with drum, see fife.
Often accompanied by accordions or bagpipes such as zampogna or müsa, it has 8-9 holes and a conical bore. In Sicily there was a larger bass version named bifora or pifara.
name: piffero

description: Known since the 15th century, it is made of a whole goat or sheep skin with fur either in or out. It has from 5 to 8 fingerholes and metalwork decorated wooden chanters.
name: cimpoi

description: It has a single chanter and drone with a bag made of a variety of animals, it has fur out and an ornamental goats head. Traditionally played at spring festivities, recently it has had a resurgence.
name: dūdmaišis

description:
For the South-American panpipe, see siku.
For the similarly named Greek bagpipe, see tsampouna.
Made of an entire sheep or goatskin, it has a single round stock that all chanters and drones are fixed into.
name: zampogna

description: Small Bulgarian/Macedonian and Balkan goat or sheep-skin bagpipe used in folk, pastoral or other traditional settings. There are many similarly named small bagpipes in this area.
name: gaida

description: Known since the 16th century, it has 3 drones; one in a separate drone pipe and two in the chanter (which as three channels), it has no bells and is mouthblown.
name: dudy podhalanskie

description:
Not to be confused with chabrette, a Limousin bagpipe.
19th century Auvergne goat-skin based bag with double reed chanter and purely decorative drone in single stock.
Early models were mouth blown, later modified to have bellows.
name: cabrette

description: An octave lower than the charango, it is the largest member of the family.
name: ronroco

description: Historically solo instrument used in traditional and ritual dances, the drones have reinforced pewter rings and the goatskin bag is covered with a colourful fabric.
name: gaita de boto

description:
For the Mallorcan bagpipe, see xeremies.
For the Latin American oboe, see chirimía.
For the mediaeval woodwind, see shawm.
Made of two tied together cane tubes with a single-reed each, they each have 4 sound-holes in front, and traditionally, one in the back.
name: reclam de xeremies

description: Having a small bag, it has a soft sound. Its chanter and two drones of differing length are made of fruitwood. It historically had single reeds, modern creations are more complex and double-reeded.
name: hümmelchen

disambiguation: Two to three drone Galician bagpipe
description: Used at-least since the 9th century, it has two to three drones with bag and pipe both decorated with fur. Used in festivals by marching players accompanied by percussion.
name: gaita gallega

description: Precursor of the cobla used in sardana, it was in use since the medieval period.
name: cobla de tres quartans

description: Often colourfully decorated, it is known since ancient times in southern Persia. It has a single reed with a double piped chanter with 6-7 holes.
name: neyanban

description: Known since atleast the 16th century, it has a long chanter, a three-segmented shoulder drone and a short blowpipe.
name: veuze

description:
Used since the 16th century, it is made of lamb, kid or in the north, sealskin. it has1-2 drones and a chanter with 4-7 fingerholes.

The name dudy/duda(s) is used for very many folk bagpipes in Europe and western Asia - see annotation(s) for more.
name: somu dūdas

description: Used in rural weddings, it has twin single reed pipes, one melody, one drone. It is becoming increasingly rare due to being displaced by Scottish Highland pipes.
name: mashak

description: From Sanabria, it is distinct from other Spanish bagpipes, with its single drone and open fingering, it is accompanied by percussion in folk music.
name: gaita sanabresa

description:
For the two tube bagless used on Ibiza, see reclam de xeremies.
For the Latin American oboe, see chirimía.
For the mediaeval woodwind, see shawm.
For the Catalan shawm also called xaramita or xirimita, see gralla.

Used historically since the middle ages on the Iberian islands, its bag is made of skin and it has one chanter with usually 3 drones, but of these usually one is real and the others are only decorative.
name: xeremies

description: Czech-Polish bellow-blown large goatskin bag with a six finger hole chanter and a long angular drone pipe that is balanced over the shoulder, the two flared pipes have inlaid metal designs and can have goat head decorations.
name: gajdy

description: Developed in Warszaw, Poland, it is used in folk music. It has two foot-operated bellows attached via metal/brass pipe; its body-bellows are only used for accents.
name: pedal accordion

description: Very similar to the xeremies, the main difference being that here all the drones are functional.
name: sac de gemecs

description:
Used since ancient times, it is a smaller half round shape with the chanter in one end and drones in the other, there are two related types; from northern Belarus and east-south Lithuania one drone one chanter both having bowed horns at the end.
Secondly; the macianka duda without horns has 3 drones in one hole instead of one.
name: matstsyanka

description:
Not to be confused with the Libyan shawm also known as zukra or zurna.
Not to be confused with mijwiz or the similar zummara.

Also do not confuse with "mizmar" a general Arabian term for several reed instruments, players of the same as well as a dance.

Used in traditional music together with drums, it has a small bag made of ewe or goat and double chanters with bells made of cowhorn.
name: mezwed

description: Used in Russian, Mari and Caucasus folk music, it has two rows of buttons in a diatonic scale, as well as additional bass buttons.
name: garmon

description:
Not to be confused with the Renaissance double-reed cornamuse.
For Italian cornamusa, see bagpipe.
While also a general term for bagpipes in French, they have two telescoping drones with single reeds and a double-reed chanter.
name: cornemuse du Centre

description: Used by shepherds and in pagan lifestyle, it has a double bore chanter with one to 2 drones, historically made of dogskin but today goat is used.
name: Magyar duda

disambiguation: Set of tuned metal plates used in western orchestra
description: Used occasionally in the western classical orchestra and theatre, it consists of several tuned aluminium, steel or bronze plates, struck to imitate the sound of bells.
name: bell plate

description: Traditionally played with the piffero in folk ensambles, the bag is usually made of kid-leather with 2 drones: a bass and a tenor and a chanter with 7-8 finger-holes.
name: piva

description: Has a bag made of goat, veal or sheepskin, and a double piped chanter collected in a single horn. Both wooden chanters have holes; one for melody, the other for drone.
name: parkapzuk

description: Generally used to accompany the traditional Catalan circle folk dance the sardana.
name: cobla

description: Early predecessor to the diatonic accordion, it was similar to the German concertina and had 4 fold bellows and brass reeds.
name: flutina

description: Used in traditional Andes music, it consists of a single row of pipes.
name: antara

description: Also known as "bock", referencing the goatskin bag, it has been in use since atleast 1340's. It has a single drone and chanter with single reeds, modern variants are bellows blown.
name: dudy

description: Used by shepherds and peoples of the southeast Black Sea region, it is droneless with parallel double chanters each with 5 fingerholes.
name: tulum

description:
For the instrument known in Italy as flicorno see saxhorn.
For the instrument known in Spain as fliscorno see flugelhorn.

Originating in Germanic polka bands, it is used today in Catalan cobla.
name: fiscorn

description:
For the similarly named Italian bagpipe, see zampogna.
Made of goatskin, it has two chanters and no drones. Its name is a reborrowing of the Italian.
name: tsampouna

description: Originally played together with the special fiddle mazanki, today with prepared violin or solo, it has a single chanter with seven finger holes and a drone pipe folded back on itself twice both ending in curved bells.
name: dudy wielkopolskie

description: Starting as a pastoral folk bellows blown bagpipe, it was developed into a complex 2, then 3 and finally 4 chanter with keyed regulators.
name: sordellina

disambiguation: ensemble of 2 violins, viola, cello and a fifth string instrument
description: Chamber ensemble of five players (two violins, one viola & one cello, then either a second viola, a second cello or a double bass).
name: string quintet

description: With a bag made of seal's stomach, 5-6 holed chanter of juniper, pine or ash and 1-2 drones, it was attested at least from the 14th century. It survived in coastal regions until its recent revival.
name: torupill
